<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chemistry student accused of blackmailing Internet company  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A graduate student at Colorado State
University was arrested Wednesday and accused of trying to extort
money, a car and free downloads from a New Jersey company that sold
digital books over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Wayne-based company, which was not named by federal
authorities, received 10 threatening e-mails from an account of
Nelson Robert Holcomb from April 20 to May 1, according to court
papers filed by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail said the sender had discovered how to download the
books for free, the papers said.
</P>
<P>
   He would not reveal the weakness to the media and the company's
partners in return for a sum equal to the retail value of the
content on the victim's Web site, a 2001 Volvo T5 Wagon, two
Diamond Rio 500 Digital Audio Players, and unlimited free downloads
of the company's content, court papers said.
</P>
<P>
   The company responded on May 2 and agreed to provide everything
but the money.
</P>
<P>
   The company had probably already notified the FBI of the threat
and was cooperating with investigators, FBI Special Agent Sandra
Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the FBI, the company got an e-mail the next day
from someone who identified himself as Rob Holcomb and said he was
the person who had contacted the company. He gave a mailing address
and work phone number at the school's chemistry department in Fort
Collins, Colo., the FBI documents said.
</P>
<P>
   On May 8, an e-mail from Holcomb's school account said he would
be willing to sign a nondisclosure agreement, the papers said.
</P>
<P>
   Holcomb was arrested at his Fort Collins, Colo., home Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Holcomb, 36, appeared in federal court in Denver on Wednesday,
where bail was set at $50,000. U.S. Magistrate Patricia A. Coan
barred Holcomb from any Internet access or from disseminating
information about the company, said Michael Drewniak, a spokesman
for the U.S. attorney's office in Newark, where the charges were
filed.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach Holcomb for comment were not successful
Wednesday. A message left at his work number in the chemistry
department was not immediately returned, and the phone at his home
in Fort Collins rang unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   Holcomb, who goes by ''Rob,'' has been a graduate student at
CSU's chemistry department since 1995, the FBI said.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted on the single charge, using the Internet to send
extortion threats, Holcomb faces up to two years in prison and a
$100,000 fine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
