<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio listens to farmers, promises support  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM KATES
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELBRIDGE, N.Y. (AP) -- Newly declared Republican Senate candidate
Rick Lazio pledged to be a vocal supporter on agricultural issues
after a morning down on the farm.
</P>
<P>
   Adopting a page from Hillary Clinton's Senate campaign playbook,
Lazio met with a group of 40 farmers in a pond-side forum Wednesday
and listened to their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am here to keep my ears open and learn and not presume to
know all the answers ... and make sure I'm responsive to the things
that you are thinking about day in and day out,'' said Lazio, who
later headed off to Washington to vote in favor of normalizing
trade relations with China -- a development the farmers applauded
for the new markets it could open to them.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering at Bob Hill's dairy farm just west of Syracuse was
reminiscent of the forums the first lady has staged across the
state over the past 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lazio aides confirmed they were planning a Sen. John
McCain-style, three-day bus trip to carry the Long Island
congressman across the state in the wake of Tuesday's state GOP
nominating convention in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Media guru Mike Murphy, who helped engineer McCain's ''Straight
Talk Express'' presidential campaign bus tours, is now working on
the Lazio campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While Lazio was visiting the farm, Clinton was in Pittsburgh for
a morning speech to the Service Employees International Union's
convention. The union is backing her candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   While not criticizing Lazio by name, the first lady attacked
Republicans who control Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every time they had an opportunity to derail progress on
education or health care or economic opportunity, they stood in the
way,'' she told 1,200 union delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio entered New York's U.S. Senate race last week following
New York City Mayor Rudy Giuliani's decision to bow out because of
his prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman began the day touring Hill's 1,000-acre dairy
farm. Unlike Clinton, who generally has traveled around the state
in a customized van driven by Secret Service agents and an
entourage in tow, Lazio drove himself to Hill's farm, accompanied
by one aide.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hillary stays with millionaires. Lazio thinks more like real
people, the people who struggle everyday to make a living,'' said
Dale Mussen, one of those who attended the pond-side forum on
Hill's property.
</P>
<P>
   As Lazio walked around the property, the seventh-generation
farmer described the hardships of modern-day farming, telling Lazio
he has already spent nearly $30,000 trying to comply with new
federal regulations governing farm waste and will spend more.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ultimately, it's going to make this a better farm, but we need
financial help. It's quite a burden for farmers to bear,'' said
Hill, who milks 100 cows and also grows corn, soybeans and alfalfa.
</P>
<P>
   The two stopped in front of a $76,000 tractor.
</P>
<P>
   ''Twenty years ago, that tractor cost $9,000. But I'm getting
the same price for milk now that I was back then. This is all
coming out of our hide. Farmers are in a tough spot,'' Hill told
the congressman.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio told Hill and the other farmers he supported a dairy
compact that would provide stable milk prices. Clinton has also
come out in favor of allowing New York to join the Northeast
Interstate Dairy Compact.
</P>
<P>
   During Lazio's 20-minute meeting with the farmers, price
volatility for agricultural products was a frequent topic,
especially for milk which has varied by as much as 40 percent in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are working with a price support system that was designed
in the 1940s,'' said Thomas Trinder, a dairy farmer from nearby
Fabius. ''We are not in the 40s. This is not a 40s economy ...
something's out of whack.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Besides, this system was not designed to help farmers. It was
designed for housewives and consumers to ensure they had a supply
of good milk,'' added Jack Russin, a dairy farmer from Madison.
</P>
<P>
   The farmers cited high fuel and utility costs, farmland
preservation and commodity surpluses among their concerns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
