<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attorney general approves Empire Blue Cross plan  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL GORMLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Empire Blue Cross and Blue Shield, which
insures many of the state's working poor among its 4.1 million
subscribers, has pledged no one will lose coverage or benefits if
it operates for profit.
</P>
<P>
   ''This shouldn't affect rates at all,'' state Attorney General
Eliot Spitzer said. On Wednesday he announced his approval of a
negotiated agreement Empire needed to move toward for-profit
status.
</P>
<P>
   ''The modified conversion plan addresses the financial needs of
the company, while at the same time preserving the charitable
assets for the benefit of the public,'' Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with Empire, once notorious for high debt and high
executive perks and salaries, protects its subscribers, he said.
The agreement includes an independent nonprofit foundation that
would own the for-profit firm and hold its stock in trust for the
state's taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The mandate of the foundation would be increased access to
health care,'' Spitzer said. Long term, ''the leaders of the
company have long believed that a conversion is a significant part
of the business model to secure the financial health of the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the effort, like Citizen Action of New York, have
said the national trend of insurers becoming for-profit companies
has led to more people without insurance while eroding the public's
faith in the health system.
</P>
<P>
   Empire, however, said that increasing access to health care has
been part of the company's foundation proposal for more than three
years, said spokeswoman Deborah Bohren. She said the company is
still resolving details with the national Blue Cross-Blue Shield
organization, which must approve any change to for-profit status.
She said she couldn't comment further because of those discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherzer, counsel for New Yorkers for Accessible Health
Coverage, said his activist group is hopeful Empire will maintain a
mission of providing more health coverage. He said many other
non-profit insurers are watching closely.
</P>
<P>
   The role of state taxpayers in Empire is considerable. For six
decades the company received tax breaks, discounted hospital rates
and other subsidies in exchange for insuring New Yorkers in need.
</P>
<P>
   The company now says it needs to covert to a more traditional
profit-making entity so it can compete for customers with other
insurance companies, Dr. Michael Stocker, Empire's chief executive
officer, has said. Empire needs its status changed to raise money
on Wall Street to buy other health care plans as well as new
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Based in New York City, Empire has 5,000 subscribers in 28
eastern and southern New York counties. It is the same Blue hit in
the early 1990s with a string of debt, high rates, consumer
dissatisfaction and high management costs. Today, consumer
advocates agree the firm is operated better.
</P>
<P>
   Empire still needs approval by the Blue Cross-Blue Shield
Association and the state Legislature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-25-00 0125 </TRAILER>
