<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seminerio says he will not support McCall for governor  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A dissident Democrat in the failed attempt
to overthrow Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver says he will not
support H. Carl McCall for governor in 2002 because the state
comptroller was publicly silent during the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Anthony Seminerio of Queens said Wednesday he will
never ''forgive'' McCall for failing to openly support former
Majority Leader Michael Bragman in the coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Seminerio said he called the comptroller twice last week when
Bragman first aired his challenge to Silver's leadership and was
told by McCall that he would support Bragman.
</P>
<P>
   ''Then I found out later on by Saturday and Sunday he changed
his mind. He went with the speaker,'' Seminerio told the Albany
radio station WROW-AM.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm Sicilian. I don't forgive,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman was an early backer of McCall -- the only black elected
to statewide office in New York -- for governor in 2002. Silver has
been thought to favor the other most likely candidate at this
point, federal Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   Seminerio said McCall ''might have gotten a commitment from
Shelly that he'll back him as governor.'' but that McCall will
''never get'' Silver's endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   In not publicly supporting Bragman, McCall has also lost
Seminerio's backing.
</P>
<P>
   ''No way will I ever get on board,'' said Seminerio, a maverick
legislator who in 1998 raised ire among fellow Democrats by
endorsing Republican George Pataki for governor over Democratic
Peter Vallone. He said Wednesday he supports U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio
over Hillary Rodham Clinton in the U.S. Senate race -- ''If Satan
ran against Hillary, I'd vote for Satan.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall spokesman Dennis Tompkins denied Seminerio's charges that
the comptroller switched sides in the Bragman-Silver dispute and
said the assemblyman ''never said he was going to back us anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Tompkins said Seminerio called McCall just once, to urge him to
support Bragman and ''expressed concern'' that if the attempted
challenge fails, he would lose his $20,000-a-year stipend as
assistant majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   ''He wanted to get the comptroller to 'call the brothers,'''
Tompkins told the Associated Press. ''The comptroller felt it was
inappropriate to turn this into a racial issue. This is a matter
that should be resolved by the Assembly majority.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall is considered an influential voice among minority
legislators in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   McCall still considers Bragman ''a very good friend'' and has a
''very strong relationship'' with the ex-majority leader, Tompkins
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said he spoke with McCall by telephone Tuesday and
assured the comptroller that ''I was his friend.''
</P>
<P>
   ''In regard with his bid to be governor, we will talk'' he said.
''As far as me believing he has tremendous experience, that's just
not something you turn on and turn off.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall's aides said he will attend Bragman's annual fund-raising
clambake in North Syracuse, being held tonight. The event regularly
attracts several thousand people and has become a must-attend event
in recent years for New York politicians.
</P>
<P>
   After initially saying he will not go to the clambake, state
Attorney General Eliot Spitzer revised his decision Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ''We endeavor not be drawn into this. However, the attorney
general had made a commitment to attend the event before and he
will honor that,'' Spitzer spokesman Darren Dopp said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton, whom Bragman has worked
hard for, will also attend the clambake, spokesman Howard Wolfson
said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Charles Schumer sent his regrets. Schumer spokeswoman
Cathie Levine said that ''as in years past, he can't make it
because of (Senate) votes'' scheduled for today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
