<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Even a Little CPR May Help  </HEADLINE>
By LINDA A. JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a surprising study released today, researchers found that
more victims of cardiac arrest may be saved when bystanders skip
mouth-to-mouth resuscitation and perform only chest compressions
until help arrives.
</P>
<P>
   The finding also could lead to major changes in the CPR
instructions dispatchers give to ordinary people who call 911.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will probably catch on quickly,'' said Dr. Russell
Harris, past president of the New Jersey chapter of the American
College of Emergency Physicians and chief of emergency medicine at
Our Lady of Lourdes Medical Center in Camden, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an excellent recommendation that may actually increase
the number of people who receive bystander CPR'' by ending worries
of catching hepatitis, AIDS or other diseases from mouth-to-mouth
contact, he said.
</P>
<P>
   University of Washington researchers found that 40 percent of
Seattle-area cardiac arrest patients who were given only chest
compressions by bystanders survived to reach a hospital, compared
with 34 percent of those who also received mouth-to-mouth
resuscitation.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 15 percent of the 241 patients receiving chest
compressions alone eventually made it home from the hospital,
compared with only about 10 percent of the 279 who received both
components of CPR, or cardiopulmonary resuscitation.
</P>
<P>
   That means that patients getting both seemed only three-quarters
as likely to make it out of the hospital alive.
</P>
<P>
   The study was published today in the New England Journal of
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Al Hallstrom, a professor of biostatistics who led the research,
said there were not enough patients in the study to say for certain
whether those getting only compressions really do fare better, but
''we are reasonably sure it's better.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallstrom said one explanation is that it takes longer for a
dispatcher to explain to someone with no medical training how to
perform both components of CPR -- 2.4 minutes vs. 1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   Harris and other experts also said it is too complicated for
many untrained people during an emergency to correctly alternate
chest compressions with mouth-to-mouth resuscitation, which
involves extending the person's neck, squeezing the nostrils shut
and blowing forcefully into the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   The study focused on cases of cardiac arrest caused by
ventricular fibrillation, a quickly fatal condition in which the
heart's main pumping chambers quiver instead of delivering blood to
the rest of the body.
</P>
<P>
   Hallstrom said giving chest compressions alone works because
when the heart goes into ventricular fibrillation, most of the
blood still contains oxygen. So compressions that keep the blood
circulating can supply the brain, heart and other organs with
enough oxygen for several minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Martin, executive director of the National Academy of
Emergency Medical Dispatch, which writes CPR instructions for
thousands of dispatchers nationwide, said that in August, the group
will debate whether untrained bystanders should be told to give
just chest compressions.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's likely going to be accepted at some time in the near
future,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   The study was done from 1992 to 1998 in the dispatch center in
Washington's King County.
</P>
<P>
   When someone witnessing an apparent cardiac arrest called 911, a
dispatcher would send help and ask if the caller knew CPR. If not,
the dispatcher would randomly instruct the caller either to give
just chest compressions, or to give mouth-to-mouth too.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers excluded cases where respiratory arrest, drug
overdose, stroke or something else was the primary problem.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Potts of the American Heart Association said the
compression-only strategy ''may be a preferred way for instructing
someone who has never had CPR training.''
</P>
<P>
   The association is drawing up new guidelines for release in
August. In the meantime, ''overall, we would still recommend that a
combination of chest compression and ventilation be used whenever
it's by a person who has had training in CPR,'' Potts said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Harris said medical personnel may end up scrapping
the term CPR because the ''pulmonary'' part -- the lungs -- would no
longer be involved.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.nejm.com
</P>
<P>
   National Academy of Emergency Medical Dispatch:
http://www.naemd.org
</P>
<P>
   American Heart Association: http://www.americanheart.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
