<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slain police remembered at annual memorial service  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERIDEN, Conn. (AP) -- It's been 50 years since Torrington police
officer Anthony Barbieri died on duty, but his son, Richard, still
has vivid memories.
</P>
<P>
   Barbieri recalled Wednesday how he would occasionally play hooky
from school so he could go fishing with his father, who worked six
days a week. Then one day when Richard Barbieri was 16, the police
chief came to his house to tell him his father had suffered a fatal
heart attack after subduing a violent young man.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's something you don't forget,'' Barbieri said, his eyes
watering.
</P>
<P>
   Barbieri joined hundreds of police officers, family members and
elected officials in remembering fallen police officers at the 12th
annual memorial ceremony at the Connecticut Police Academy.
</P>
<P>
   His father's name was one of two added to a monument honoring
123 officers from local, state and federal law enforcement agencies
who died in the line of duty in Connecticut since 1880.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what this monument is all about-- not forgetting,'' said
former Governor William A. O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   Barbieri died 50 years ago, but his name was inadvertently left
off the monument. After his son noticed the oversight, the name was
added to the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm gratified,'' Barbieri said. ''It's just very heartwarming
that he gets recognized after all these years.''
</P>
<P>
   Also honored at the ceremony Wednesday was Middletown Sgt.
George Dingwall, who was killed in January when his cruiser crashed
while chasing two robbery suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Dingwall was an exemplary police officer who loved his job and
family, Middletown Police Chief Ed Brymer said.
</P>
<P>
   Bagpipes and the sound of taps punctuated the ceremony. Two red
roses were placed on a blue and yellow flower bed shaped as a badge
in honor of Barbieri and Dingwall, while police officers in white
gloves retired a flag of honor.
</P>
<P>
   Barbieri along with Dingwall's widow, Kim, and their two
children, were led from the indoor ceremony to the monument to
witness the unveiling of the two names.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker after speaker declared the 123 officers heroes. Their
names were read with a drum roll as officers saluted each one.
Officials urged the public to visit the monument, saying the
sacrifices and risks of police officers are often taken for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   ''We forget the dangers they face,'' said Lt. Gov. M. Jodi Rell.
''We take for granted their courage, their strength and their
presence.''
</P>
<P>
   As he looked out at the sea of blue uniforms, Barbieri said any
of the officers could face the fate of his father.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's kind of sobering,'' Barbieri said. ''They put their lives
on the line day in and day out.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the monument, Barbieri also has the bench his
father sat on in the police station where he died.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every time I look at that bench,'' he said, ''I think of my
father.''
</P>
<P>
   Middletown held its own ceremony to honor Dingwall Wednesday,
naming a street in his memory.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sgt. Dingwall is in the hearts and souls of everyone of us and
will never be forgotten,'' Brymer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
