<DOCNO> APW20000525.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Trade Fence-Sitters Pressured  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The final fencesitters on the China trade bill
took calls from the White House and intense lobbying from both
business and organized labor. Even actor Arnold Schwarzenegger
contacted undecided lawmakers to urge them to vote for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end it was often local interests that determined the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was an issue of weighing the elements,'' said Rep. James
Maloney, D-Conn., who just hours before the vote to grant permanent
trade status to China decided he couldn't support it.
</P>
<P>
   For his state, he said, ''gains would occur in service
industries and losses in manufacturing, and for Connecticut that's
kind of our weak spot.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I evaluated the effects on employment in my district and it
was not favorable,'' said Rep. Rick Boucher, D-Va., saying it
finally came down to concerns about job losses in his district's
furniture and sewing factories.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Rep. David McIntosh, R-Ind., who is running
for governor of his state, said he decided to support the bill
after talking to companies exporting to China and considering a big
boost in agriculture exports. ''The best thing for Indiana was to
vote yes.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 lawmakers had yet to declare their intentions by
Wednesday morning, leaving in suspense the outcome of the bill. It
passed 237-197.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody's calling,'' said Rep. Robert Scott, D-Va., who
voted against the bill after careful study of the economic pros and
cons. ''You make more than half the people mad. Some because you
didn't vote their way and some because you didn't come out
earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Some acknowledged that their vote might not be welcomed at home.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the first time since I've been in Congress that the
way I'm voting is not going to be understood by a lot of my
constituents,'' said Rep. Jim DeMint, a freshman Republican from
South Carolina who voted ''yes.''
</P>
<P>
   DeMint said up to three-fourths of people in his district may
oppose the China bill and ''a lot of my supporters in the textile
industry and the religious community don't understand'' his stance
that the legislation will encourage the opening of China's market
and not result in U.S. job losses.
</P>
<P>
   Maloney said that while he had gotten calls from people saying
they would not support him if he voted against the bill, ''I don't
think it's an issue that cuts with voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew Research Center for the People
and the Press, agreed that while a Pew poll taken earlier this
month showed about half of Americans opposed to the China trade
deal, feelings toward China don't run deep. ''Public opinion isn't
really in the game here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But for many Democrats, a ''yes'' vote risked antagonizing labor
groups, who strongly opposed a bill they said would threaten
American jobs.
</P>
<P>
   For others, the final decision came down to the issue of whether
China deserved normal trade status. ''Free trade alone, without
consideration for human rights, basic labor standards and
environmental protection, will only encourage a race to the
bottom,'' said Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn., ranking Democrat on the
International Relations Committee. He waited until Wednesday to
announce his ''no'' vote.
</P>
<P>
   To win supporters, President Clinton made personal calls and
business groups assigned a lobbyist to each undecided lawmaker.
Significant money was spent in the effort to win passage, said U.S.
Chamber of Commerce President Tom Donohue. ''This was done on
retail, one vote at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton issued a statement individually thanking Rep. Gregory
Meeks, D-N.Y., who voted for the bill after joining an
administration-sponsored trip to China, and attending a state
dinner for the South African president.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, George W. Bush, the likely GOP presidential nominee
who was campaigning Wednesday in Michigan, called Rep. Ernie
Fletcher, R-Ky., to urge him to vote for the bill. He did.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House site: http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO site: http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
