<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton and Lazio disagree where Clinton and Giuliani didn't  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- When Rudolph Giuliani and Hillary Rodham Clinton
were New York's Senate candidates, the National Abortion Rights
Action League of New York refused to make an endorsement in the
race because both the first lady and the mayor were unequivocally
pro-choice.
</P>
<P>
   And NARAL-NY's director, Kelli Conlin, had been careful to
attend events supporting both candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But with Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island replacing Giuliani as
the GOP candidate, voters passionate about abortion and a number of
other issues -- gun control, gay rights and the environment --
suddenly have a starker choice.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio -- who in just three days has made the environment a major
campaign theme -- is viewed as an important ally by groups like
Friends of the Earth for his votes against strip-mining and for
cleaning up Long Island Sound. But he does not share Clinton's
unequivocal support for gun licensing, a hate-crimes law that would
increase penalties for gay bias attacks, or Medicaid-funded
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Based on Rick Lazio's past votes, New Yorkers have to be wary
of his pro-choice proclamations,'' NARAL-NY's deputy director
Robert Jaffe said Wednesday. ''Rick Lazio, time and time again, has
voted to strip away women's right to choose.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Wednesday there were clear differences between the
two candidates and said she would raise them repeatedly in the
coming months.
</P>
<P>
   ''Abortion rights will be an important issue in this race,'' she
said in an interview with The New York Times. The Times reported
today that NARAL's local and national chapters would endorse
Clinton at a news conference this morning.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Clinton asserted that she would not vote to
confirm Supreme Court judges who do not believe that Roe v. Wade,
the Supreme Court decision legalizing abortion, should be upheld.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio opposes late-term abortions (called partial-birth
abortions by critics) and federal funding for abortions for poor
women.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do not want to criminalize abortion,'' Lazio said in an
upstate campaign swing Monday. ''On the other hand, I want to make
it rarer and I don't think just because we have a right, that we
need to subsidize that right.''
</P>
<P>
   Anti-abortion groups like New Yorkers for Constitutional
Freedoms, which represents 2,000 evangelical churches, are cheered
by his position.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before, when there was just Giuliani and Clinton, our people
were having a hard time deciding what to do,'' said the Rev. Duane
Motley, founder of the group. ''But Lazio is a good possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   On gun control, Lazio is a strong enough proponent to have
earned himself a ''D-minus'' from the National Rifle Association.
He supports the Brady Bill, assault-weapons ban and trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   But Lazio calls licensing ''invasive'' and says he hasn't seen a
registration program that's ''workable.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We had not taken a position on the New York Senate race prior
to this. We probably would have stayed out,'' said Joe Sudbay of
Handgun Control in Washington, which would have been thrilled to
have either Clinton or Giuliani win.
</P>
<P>
   But Lazio's opposition to handgun licensing and registration --
which is the law in New York -- is ''troubling,'' Sudbay says. ''We
want people who are going to be with us on all the major issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, one of Lazio's most prominent
Republican supporters, rejects the notion that voters who care
about gun control or abortion will have a problem pulling the lever
for Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's nitpicking,'' D'Amato said. ''His overall record is a
solid one. It's a middle-of-the-road, sensible, conservative one.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups are happy to hear Lazio making their
concerns a campaign priority. Clinton held one recent event on acid
rain in the Adirondacks, but has focused most of her campaign on
child welfare, education, health and job growth.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until now, this has been an absentee issue in this Senate
debate,'' said Deb Callahan, president of the League of
Conservation Voters. ''Rick Lazio has a strong record on
environmental issues and we're pleased to see someone like him in
the race. We consider him to be a good friend. He will absolutely
raise the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The group endorsed Lazio in his Congressional race, but like
other environmental groups, is waiting to interview both candidates
before deciding on a Senate endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, gay rights advocates are disappointed with Lazio. The
Human Rights Campaign, a gay advocacy group in Washington, gave
Lazio a rating of 18 out of 100 last year, down sharply from his 50
percent rating in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While neither Clinton nor Giuliani had a voting record to
compare, both had ''been supportive of some core issues on the
lesbian-gay agenda -- comprehensive civil rights protection,
domestic partnership, recognition of the rights of gays to serve
openly in the military, and support of hate-crimes legislation,''
said Tim Sweeney of the Empire State Pride Agenda. ''That is no
longer the case with the entrance of Rep. Lazio.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ''If you can't be an advocate that will persuade the
Republican Party to modernize and update, then what's the rationale
for a gay person to vote for you?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
