<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Boosts Security at Its Offices  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Responding to suggestions from a House panel,
the FBI has boosted security at its headquarters here and other
locations.
</P>
<P>
   The steps were ''based on recommendations received yesterday
from the crime subcommittee of the House Judiciary Committee. ...
No specific threat gives rise to this announcement,'' the bureau
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Henceforth, at FBI headquarters on Pennsylvania Avenue, police
and law enforcement officers from outside the FBI will have to
surrender their weapons before entering unless they have been given
permanent building passes. Also, the guard post on the street will
verify visitors' picture identification and which FBI employee they
are visiting, rather than waiting to do that when they reach an
escort desk inside the J. Edgar Hoover Building.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the popular FBI Tour will not be required to have an
appointment with an FBI employee, but they will continue to pass
through a metal detector, have their packages searched and be
escorted inside the building.
</P>
<P>
   The tightened security was prompted by an investigation by the
General Accounting Office, whose investigators, posing as armed law
enforcement officers, carried unsearched briefcases past security
guards at Reagan National Airport and secure government buildings
including the State Department, the FBI and the Pentagon, several
newspapers reported Thursday. The reports appeared in the
Washington Post, the Dallas Morning News, the Washington Times, the
Miami Herald, the Chicago Tribune and the Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators' findings were shared at a closed-door
briefing on Capitol Hill Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Posing as plainclothes officers of the FBI, Drug Enforcement
Administration and New York City Police Department and using
counterfeit identification obtained on the Internet, the
investigators were waved around metal detectors when they announced
they were carrying weapons, the Post said. Some investigators
roamed freely through buildings and easily located the office of
each agency's head -- only at the CIA were they unable to reach the
agency head's office.
</P>
<P>
   While they carried no actual weapons, the undercover
investigators were able to drive a rental van into the interior
courtyard of the Justice Department. The investigators made their
way up to Attorney General Janet Reno's office suite, although she
wasn't there, the newspaper said. At Reagan National and Orlando
International airports, the phony officers weren't searched and
received permits to carry weapons aboard airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the FBI's increased security precautions apply to other
bureau locations as well.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI said these steps were in addition to others taken over
the past five years to increase security around the Hoover building
in response to terrorist bombings like those at the Oklahoma City
federal building and the World Trade Center in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau noted that all parking alongside the building has
been eliminated, the courtyard has been closed to the public,
concrete security barriers have been placed outside, and metal
detectors, X-ray machines, package searches and photo
identification requirements have been implemented during that time.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, for the security of building and of tourists
waiting on line for the tour, FBI police protection outside the
building has been increased. The tour was suspended for a couple
months last summer because of nonspecific threats while the bureau
decided how to protect people waiting outside to take the tour.
Tours resumed after extra police and dogs were posted outside.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-25-00 0733 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
