<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 08:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> City continues investigation into collapse  </HEADLINE>
By GINA CAPPELLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- City officials would not comment on reports
that a man operating a nightclub on Pier 34 on the Delaware River
was warned that the pier was unstable the day before it collapsed
and killed three women.
</P>
<P>
   ''That is a police investigation and we are staying away from
that,'' mayoral Chief of Staff Stephanie Franklin-Suber said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce Construction Corp. president Terry Zettle said Tuesday
that his company gave the operator of the nightclub, Heat, a
written report stating that the foundation was slanting toward the
river and there were twisted metal supports.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let me put it this way, we were amazed that they had people on
that pier after we told them of what we found. We surely didn't
think they were going to have people on that pier,'' Zettle told
WPVI-TV.
</P>
<P>
   The Bridgeport, N.J., company was hired May 15 by club operator
Eli Karetny to look into cracks in the pier's concrete surface,
Zettle said, adding that he sent two divers and a supervisor on May
16 to examine the pier. He said his company reported its findings
to the nightclub management the following day.
</P>
<P>
   Three people were killed and several dozen injured May 18 -- the
day after Zettle said his company gave the report to Karetny -- when
the pier supporting the new nightclub Heat crashed into the
Delaware River.
</P>
<P>
   Zettle said a senior officer of his company was questioned by
homicide detectives Monday, but he declined to name the employee. A
copy of Commerce's report to Karetny has been given to homicide
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Police are attempting to determine whether criminal charges are
warranted in the case. They said that a final determination might
not be made for weeks, if not months.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Asbell, owner of the pier, said Wednesday his attorney
advised him not to comment on the report. Asbell's attorney, John
L. Jenkins, did not return phone calls Wednesday. Nightclub owner
Eli Karetny and Karetny's lawyer, Robert Lane, did not immediately
return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Ed McLaughlin, commissioner of the city's Department of Licenses
and Inspections, said during a press conference Wednesday that he
learned that an engineering study was completed in 1992 on Pier 34
before the structure was built.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't seen that report yet, but we do want to look at what
was done in the survey,'' McLaughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin also said that the underwater surveys were completed
on Pier 34 by Urban Engineers Inc., the company investigating the
collapse for the city. McLaughlin expects to have a better idea of
what caused the pier to collapse by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   ''Divers continue to take photos in the water,'' McLaughlin
said. ''The sonar and the hydrographic surveys have been completed.
Those surveys will tell us how the pier fell.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials also said Wednesday they are continuing to
investigate all the piers in the city as ordered by Mayor John
Street. There are about 180 piers along the city's waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin-Suber said Pier 31 North, owned by Penn's Landing
Corp., and leased to the city's Streets and Fleets Department, was
investigated and found to be safe after a city employee noticed
cracks on the pier's surface.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no reason for alarm or concern,'' Franklin-Suber
said. ''There is no safety risk on this pier.''
</P>
<P>
   But, to ensure the safety of the city's employees who work on
the pier, Franklin-Suber said the city will conduct an underwater
investigation of Pier 31. She could not estimate how much the
survey would cost the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-25-00 0809 </TRAILER>
