<HEADLINE> Dow Down 6; Nasdaq Up 80  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in early trading today as
jittery investors once again moved money from one sector to
another. Technology stocks rose, buoying the Nasdaq, but financial
shares stumbled.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq
composite index was up 80.86 to 3,351.47.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Dow Jones industrial
average was down 6.17 at 10,529.18, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 8.87 at 1,407.92.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks were continuing a rebound that began Wednesday
as investors started channeling money into stocks that have tumbled
in the past few weeks. Cisco Systems was up 2] at 57{, and Oracle
rose 3~ to 68[.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts fear the sector's recovery may be fragile, because the
interest rate worries that undermined technology stocks in the
first place are still haunting the market. Most market watchers
anticipate choppy trading for at least another week, with no clear
leadership from any one sector.
</P>
<P>
   Today, bank stocks that have thrived lately were mostly lower.
Citigroup fell 1 1/16 to 60 5/16 after Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
cut its rating on the stock to ''outperform'' from ''strong buy.''
</P>
<P>
   The market was little affected by the Commerce Department's
report that the U.S. economy, powered by brisk consumer and
government spending, grew at a robust 5.4 percent annual rate
during the first three months of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation-wary investors were most interested in an inflation
gauge tied to the gross domestic product, which rose at an annual
rate of 3.1 percent in the first quarter. The market had
anticipated a slightly bigger increase. Surging energy prices
accounted for most of the gain.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 130.66 million
shares, ahead of Wednesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 7.36 to 469.10.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1.3 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 1.9 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 1.2 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
2.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
