<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Change Sought In Poor Kids Dental  </HEADLINE>
By TOM VERDIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Calling it a neglected epidemic, health officials
say California's children suffer twice as much dental disease as
youngsters nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   A plan to be released today recommends attacking the problem by
increasing use of fluoride in public water supplies, improving
access to dental care, expanding insurance coverage and educating
parents about keeping their kids' teeth healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Many childhood diseases such as measles, mumps and whooping
cough are well-managed or have been nearly wiped out by aggressive
prevention, according to the report by the nonprofit Dental Health
Foundation. Oral diseases, however, remain relatively forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the most common disease in children, and from a public
health point of view what makes it tragic is it's preventable,''
said Dr. Larry Platt, executive director of the Oakland-based
group.
</P>
<P>
   The group timed the report's release to coincide with the first
ever U.S. Surgeon General's report on oral health nationwide, also
due out today.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics presented by the foundation paint a grim picture of
dental health among the state's children:
</P>
<P>
   --Untreated tooth decay was found in 53 percent of children in
grades kindergarten through third, 54 percent of 10th graders and
27 percent of children ages 2 to 5.
</P>
<P>
   --Minority children fared worst, with 40 percent of preschoolers
and 75 percent of elementary-aged children needing dental care.
</P>
<P>
   --More than a quarter of preschool and elementary children and
more than 40 percent of high school students have no dental
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have to accept this as normal,'' said Dr. Jared Fine,
Alameda County's director of public dental health and chairman of a
committee that created the recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Adding fluoride to more municipal water supplies is one of the
key recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 state law required fluoridation in public water systems
with at least 10,000 connections. Since then Los Angeles and
Sacramento have been the only large cities to add it, said Dr.
David Nelson of the California Department of Health Services'
office of oral health.
</P>
<P>
   The cost to bring fluoride to the rest is close to $180 million,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The report will be posted Friday at
www.dentalhealthfoundation.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-25-00 1100 </TRAILER>
