<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 12:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish Government in Crisis  </HEADLINE>
By BEATA PASEK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- The embattled Solidarity bloc withdrew
support for Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek on Thursday to try to keep
the ruling coalition intact.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis in the 2{-year Solidarity-led coalition was set off
Monday night when the tiny Freedom Union party threatened to leave
the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Freedom Union leaders, led by Finance Minister Leszek
Balcerowicz, say they lost confidence in the prime minister, who is
unable to control his deputies in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom Union party's executive council must decide Sunday
whether to formally leave the government.
</P>
<P>
   But Solidarity leaders, fearing a government collapse could
return the ex-Communist Democratic Left Alliance to power, agreed
to negotiate with the Freedom Union and sacrifice every minister.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Solidarity board has agreed to negotiate with the Freedom
Union replacing the whole government,'' Solidarity leader Jan
Rokita told national radio Plus.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his tenuous position, Buzek continued his duties,
meeting with his Irish counterpart Bertie Ahern.
</P>
<P>
   Buzek repeated to reporters he will resign ''if there is such a
need. It's important that this coalition lasts because it has done
lots of work.''
</P>
<P>
   The splintered Solidarity bloc formed the coalition government
with the business-oriented Freedom Union in 1997 to prepare Poland
for European Union membership, a task Solidarity alleges was
neglected by the previous post-communist government.
</P>
<P>
   Buzek, however, was unable to unify Solidarity deputies who
voted several times against government-backed reforms deemed
crucial for Poland's economic progress by Balcerowicz, the finance
minister.
</P>
<P>
   Balcerowicz has demanded concrete actions from Solidarity, such
as eliminating laws that hamper state finance and resolving the
crisis in Warsaw's local government.
</P>
<P>
   A poll published in Thursday's daily Rzeczpospolita said if
early elections were held, the post-communist opposition would get
more than 30 percent support to 15 percent for Solidarity. The poll
of 610 respondents has a margin of error of plus or minus 4
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-25-00 1210 </TRAILER>
