<HEADLINE> Venezuela Elections May Be Put Off  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- President Hugo Chavez said today that
elections later this week in Venezuela will probably be postponed
because of technical problems.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuelans are set to elect a president, legislature,
governors, and other positions in balloting Sunday. However,
election officials have been unable to fix the computers used for
vote tabulation.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the delay, Chavez said: ''I hope this doesn't
happen but it is probable that it will.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez cannot postpone the vote. However, the Supreme Court was
expected to rule today on whether to move back the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Election authorities said Wednesday they expected to correct the
problems and begin testing the computer system. But international
observers said today that glitches remained.
</P>
<P>
   ''At this hour I do not believe the conditions are appropriate
to hold elections,'' Patricio Lombardi, a spokesman for the
Organization of American States mission in Venezuela, told The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a Venezuelan air force jet flew from the United
States to Caracas with equipment authorities said could salvage
this weekend's vote.
</P>
<P>
   The elections are required by a new constitution pushed through
by President Hugo Chavez last year that calls for many public
positions to be ''re-legitimized.''
</P>
<P>
   The electoral process has also come under fire because the
electoral council was hand-picked by Chavez's leftist coalition in
an exercise widely criticized as undemocratic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
