<HEADLINE> Clinton Tackles Prescription Drugs  </HEADLINE>
By SONYA ROSS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton appealed Thursday for
Republicans in Congress to build on the momentum of the China trade
vote and take up his proposal for prescription drug coverage under
Medicare. ''I'm here asking for cooperation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton gathered Democratic congressional leaders in the White
House Rose Garden for ''a show of unity and a demonstration of
resolve'' on the prescription drug plan. The president rejected as
unfair a GOP alternative that limits the benefit according to
income, but held open the prospect of compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are some people in their party who really would like to
work with us,'' Clinton said. ''Look, for the last five years, we
surprised everybody -- including ourselves -- a time or two and
really had breakthroughs and (have) gotten stuff done.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm here asking for cooperation, and I think I speak for our
leaders and our members,'' Clinton continued. ''We're interested in
doing something, so we're willing to do what we can to do our part
on that.''
</P>
<P>
   His appeal came a day after the House -- thanks to strong
Republican support -- approved a major trade deal with China that he
has made a top priority of his final year in office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was joined in the Rose Garden by his secretaries of
treasury and health and human services, House Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt, D-Mo., Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., and
about a dozen other Democratic lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no reason that Congress cannot take the necessary
steps,'' Clinton said. ''We know we can afford it and we think the
time to act is now.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been pressing Congress to add drug coverage to
Medicare that any senior citizen could get for about $25 a month.
An alternative being developed by House Republicans would help
senior citizens get private drug insurance and provide subsidies
for those with the lowest incomes and highest bills.
</P>
<P>
   The House has passed legislation extending prescription drug
benefits to 1.4 million Medicare-eligible retirees and family
members. The Democrats said that proposal was good but
insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said the prescription drug proposal is ''stuck in the
quagmire of Republican resistance.'' He described Democrats as
frustrated over the lack of progress on their health proposals with
only 23 legislative days remaining before this summer's political
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their prescription drug plan is neither responsible nor
real,'' Gephardt said. ''They continue to advocate massive tax cuts
(that would) plunge us back into deficit spending. Their approach
simply won't help the millions of seniors who need help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
