<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Phony Cops Breach Federal Security  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal investigators carrying fake law
enforcement credentials penetrated the security of 19 government
installations and two commercial airports, a congressional audit
reported today. In many cases they were waved by metal detectors.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were able to enter 18 of the 21 sites on the first attempt.
The remaining three required a second visit before we were able to
penetrate the sites,'' said the report from the General Accounting
Office.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators penetrated security at Reagan National Airport
outside Washington, at the Orlando, Fla., international airport and
at government offices including the FBI, CIA, State Department,
Justice Department and Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO, an investigative arm of Congress, prepared the report
for the House Judiciary subcommittee on crime.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee had asked that the GAO to investigate the
potential security risk posed by the use of stolen or counterfeit
law enforcement badges and credentials. Lawmakers had expressed
concern that such badges and credentials are readily available on
the Internet and from other public sources.
</P>
<P>
   ''At no time during the undercover visits were our agents' bogus
credentials or badges challenged by anyone,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The report brought an immediate reaction from Rep. Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., who chairs the House Judiciary Committee. ''I hope this
startling report will focus new attention on enhancing our security
of the public buildings housing our governmental agencies,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   At all 21 sites, the agents who took part in the operation
''could have carried weapons. listening devices, explosives,
chemical/biological agents, devices and/or other such
items/materials,'' the study said.
</P>
<P>
   At each site, the agents declared themselves as armed law
enforcement officers and gained entry by avoiding screening, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   An immediate result of the investigation was a tightening of
security at FBI headquarters, the Justice Department and at the
Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was surprised that there were so many'' places they could
get into, Attorney General Janet Reno told her weekly news
conference. But she added, ''Anytime you expose vulnerabilities,
it's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The report said 16 of the sites housed the offices of cabinet
secretaries or agency heads. At 15, ''our undercover agents were
able to stand immediately outside the suites of the Cabinet
secretary or agency head,'' GAO said, adding that in five
instances, the agents were able to gain entry into the suites.
</P>
<P>
   ''At 15 of the sites, our agents entered a restroom in the
vicinity of these offices and could have left a valise containing
weapons,'' the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said Justice security had been revised but declined to
describe the changes. She said Justice officials were looking at
the availability of false credentials on the Internet to see how
the investigators were able to get credentials.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators were sent out at the request of Rep. Bill
McCollum, R-Fla., who has introduced legislation to increase the
penalty for using fake law enforcement credentials.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Justice official, who requested anonymity, said GAO
investigators using fake New York City police sergeants'
credentials tried twice to get into the main Justice building and
were turned away once when no appointment for them could be
verified.
</P>
<P>
   But they came back to the automobile gate with a van, showed the
fake New York credentials and said they were armed and were waived
inside and allowed to park in the courtyard, this official said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We always want to treat other law enforcement officers with
absolute courtesy,'' this official said, ''but this was a wake-up
call that we have a problem with professional courtesy for other
law enforcement personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   Henceforth, state and local officers will be required to check
their guns before entering Justice and go through metal detectors
and have their bags X-rayed. If they are coming to make an arrest,
they will be able to keep their guns but will be escorted, this
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI said Wednesday its new security steps were ''based on
recommendations received yesterday from the crime subcommittee of
the House Judiciary Committee. ... No specific threat gives rise to
this announcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Henceforth, at FBI headquarters on Pennsylvania Avenue, police
and law enforcement officers from outside the FBI will have to
surrender their weapons before entering unless they have been given
permanent building passes.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the guard post on the street will verify visitors' picture
identification and which FBI employee they are visiting, rather
than waiting to do that when they reach an escort desk inside the
J. Edgar Hoover Building.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the popular FBI Tour will not be required to have an
appointment with an FBI employee, but they will continue to pass
through a metal detector, have their packages searched and be
escorted inside the building.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Department spokesman Glenn Flood said today the Pentagon
has long followed a practice of allowing federal law enforcement
officers -- but not state or local officers -- to enter the building
without question simply by showing their badges. This policy is now
under review as a result of the GAO investigation, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-25-00 1234 </TRAILER>
