<DOCNO> APW20000525.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slain AP Journalist Knew of Dangers  </HEADLINE>
By TIM SULLIVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Miguel Gil Moreno de Mora had no
illusions about the danger involved as his work as an Associated
Press Television News cameraman took him from one war zone to
another.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every minute of every day you think you are going to die,'' he
wrote last December while reporting from Chechnya's capital,
Grozny, during intense, round-the-clock bombardments by Russian
planes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every day ... I met, filmed or gave cigarettes to people who
were dead by the next morning. This is the horrific reality of life
in Grozny at the dawn of the new millennium,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Moreno de Mora survived Chechnya and other brutal conflicts
from Kosovo to Iraq to Congo. On Wednesday, he was killed in an
ambush in war-ravaged Sierra Leone. He was 32.
</P>
<P>
   Maria de Patrocinio Macian Blaya, Gil Moreno de Mora's mother,
said from her home in Barcelona, Spain that her son was a ''truly
extraordinary person.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I am filled with overwhelming sadness and grief, but in the
end I find solace in the fact that Miguel was doing the job he
loved and died doing the work he felt ordained for,'' she said.
''He felt his mission was to give voice to those who did not have
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Gil Moreno de Mora provided news dispatches from war zones where
he often was the only journalist to witness dramatic events.
</P>
<P>
   He had been in Sierra Leone for the past two weeks, spending
much of that time on or near the shifting front lines. On Monday,
in one of his last stories, he was among the first journalists to
see several mutilated corpses that appeared to be the bodies of
U.N. peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The gruesome find was just outside Rogberi Junction, not far
from the spot where he and Reuters correspondent Kurt Schork were
killed.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Moreno de Mora, who was from Barcelona, Spain, was a
corporate lawyer who practiced briefly before becoming a cameraman.
He got his first break as a free-lancer in Bosnia. Needing press
accreditation, but struggling to find an employer to back him, he
eventually managed to wangle a press card on behalf of a motorcycle
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ''Miguel told me once that he felt he was contributing more to
the world as a journalist than as a lawyer,'' said Aida
Cerkez-Robinson, an Associated Press reporter who worked with Gil
Moreno de Mora in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said he was helping the innocent people trapped in a war
more by telling the world about their destiny. This was his motive.
I think it carried him from one war to another.''
</P>
<P>
   Before and during NATO's war against Yugoslavia last year, Gil
Moreno de Mora spent months with members of the Kosovo Liberation
Army, often living in the woods with the fighters for weeks at a
time. He was the only Western cameraman to remain in Kosovo's
capital, Pristina, when NATO bombed the region last year.
</P>
<P>
   His work in Kosovo earned him the 1999 Royal Television
Society's cameraman of the year award in Britain, an honor he
received just last month.
</P>
<P>
   The previous year, Gil Moreno de Mora won an award given in
memory of another cameraman -- the Rory Peck Award -- for his
coverage in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Moreno de Mora was the 25th AP journalist to die in the line
of duty since the organization was founded in 1848.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Moreno de Mora, who was based in London, was the second APTN
staffer killed in Sierra Leone in the past 16 months. Producer
Myles Tierney was fatally shot at a checkpoint in Freetown on Jan.
10, 1999, an attack that also seriously injured Associated Press
West Africa bureau chief Ian Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Moreno de Mora, who worked with Tierney in Africa for two
years, paid tribute to his colleague shortly after his death.
</P>
<P>
   ''Myles understood people in pain,'' he said. ''He cared for
them because each was an individual to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigel Baker, head of news for APTN, said the same could be said
of Gil Moreno de Mora himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''Miguel was intuitive, bold and one of the most intelligent
cameramen of his generation,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He went to the world's most dangerous places but didn't make a
move without weighing up the reasons for doing it and his options.
He had immense respect from all who knew him not just for his work
but because he was a deeply modest man who would help anybody he
could.''
</P>
</TEXT>
