<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Bans Pop Star's Ads  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwan's new president expressed regret
Thursday that China has banned advertisements featuring a pop star
who sang the national anthem at his inauguration last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   China's decision to pull Taiwanese singer Chang Huei-mei's
Sprite soft drink ads from billboards, newspapers and TV broadcasts
was ''incomprehensible,'' President Chen Shui-bian said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That a citizen of the Republic of China singing the anthem in
her own country should receive such a reaction is regrettable,''
Chen said, referring to Taiwan by its official name.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like treating your own compatriot, your own brother or
sister as an enemy,'' Chen said.
</P>
<P>
   China and Taiwan split amid civil war 51 years ago. However,
cultural exchanges have flourished in recent years, and Chang --
known as A-mei -- has a big following on the mainland. Her tour of
China last year was a huge success.
</P>
<P>
   Chang's ads ran for at least a month on China Central Television
before being pulled Saturday just after her appearance at the
inauguration, an event that was carefully watched by Beijing
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The anthem Chang sang was composed on the mainland before the
two sides separated. It is seen as a symbol of Taiwan's link to the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between China and Taiwan have grown strained following
Chen's election victory in March. China distrusts Chen because he
was once a vocal supporter of Taiwan independence. Beijing has
repeatedly threatened to attack if the island seeks a permanent
break.
</P>
<P>
   Coca Cola, which manufactures Sprite, confirmed the ban of the
30-second TV spots by Chinese television and said the company would
not contest the decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-25-00 1249 </TRAILER>
