<DOCNO> APW20000525.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elian's Miami Relatives Moving  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- The Miami relatives of Elian Gonzalez are moving
out of the Little Havana home made famous by the media hordes and
protesters who camped out in front of the bungalow during the five
months the 6-year-old Cuban boy was living there.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are moving,'' family spokesman Armando Gutierrez said.
</P>
<P>
   The family could move from the rented home next month if
renovations on their new home in West Miami and the sale of the
property are completed by then.
</P>
<P>
   The family has lived in the modest 1952 two-bedroom,
one-bathroom home for more than a decade, but say they have felt
uncomfortable there since the April 22 federal raid that removed
Elian from the home and reunited him with his Cuban father.
</P>
<P>
   Elian and his Cuban family have been living in a secluded
Maryland retreat for the last month, but are expected to soon move
to a Washington, D.C., estate, an American supporter said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The family is awaiting a decision from the 11th Circuit U.S.
Court of Appeals in Atlanta on the Miami relatives' request for
asylum for the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's swing set already has been moved to the back yard of his
relatives' new home. Posts have been dug for a fence because the
family says it wants privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''People I don't know wave to me if I'm standing outside'' the
Little Havana home, said Lazaro Gonzalez, Elian's great uncle.
</P>
<P>
   The West Miami residence, a 1948 two-bedroom, two-bathroom home
that previously was in foreclosure, was bought at an auction in
February for $112,500 by a real estate investor and friend of the
Gonzalez family.
</P>
<P>
   Plans are to sell the renovated home to Delfin Gonzalez,
Lazaro's brother, who will in turn lease it, with an option to buy,
to Lazaro, his wife, Angela, and daughter, Marisleysis.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement is necessary because Delfin qualifies for a
mortgage and Lazaro is not currently employed, The Miami Herald
said in Thursday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   In related developments:
</P>
<P>
   -- At her weekly news conference, Attorney General Janet Reno
said she had no plans to meet with members of Miami's exiled Cuban
community during a trip to Florida Thursday evening. Reno said she
would prefer to wait until tensions over the Gonzalez case subside
before meeting with the community, adding that she has not been
invited to meet with any of its representatives. ''I want to do it
in a reasonable, thoughtful way that respects feelings and tensions
and gives people time to talk out issues,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   -- Cuban American groups plan to protest Reno's speech Thursday
evening in the Bal Harbor section of Miami. Brothers to the Rescue,
a volunteer group that flies over the Florida Straits looking for
Cubans leaving their homeland by sea, planned a street protest as
well as a fly-over by their small planes. The Democracy Movement,
an anti-Castro group that helped stage protests outside the
Gonzalez home, said it will have protesters in the street and
aboard a flotilla in the Atlantic Ocean, across the beach from the
hotel where Reno is set to speak.
</P>
<P>
   -- Newly released U.S. Coast Guard records show that a doctor who
examined Elian shortly after the boy was rescued at sea told
immigration authorities he probably had been in the water less than
24 hours. Elian was rescued Thanksgiving Day after his boat
capsized, killing his mother and several others fleeing Cuba for
the United States. He was believed to have spent more than 50 hours
in the water, but a log entry by an unidentified Coast Guard
official said, ''Doctor said the boy wasn't in the water 24 hrs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
