<HEADLINE> Philippine Hostages' Morale Low  </HEADLINE>
By JIM GOMEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOLO, Philippines (AP) -- After more than a month in the hands of
Muslim rebels in the jungle, hostages' hopes are dimming and
frustrations are rising even though formal negotiations could begin
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody is fed up,'' South African hostage Callie Strydom
told reporters who were allowed to visit the Abu Sayyaf rebels'
hide-out Thursday. ''We are being used as pawns between the
political side and this group.''
</P>
<P>
   Captive Risto Vahanen the hostages' mood ''has been going down
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Yesterday, today, we have actually lost our hope in the
proceedings, in the negotiations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf's Commander Robot said that the length of the
hostages' confinement was up to the government.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are still waiting for the results of the negotiations,''
Robot said. ''We also want to release the hostages as soon as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief government negotiator Robert Aventajado had high hopes for
the talks set to open Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the conditions are right. The Abu Sayyaf trusts that
the military will not attack, and the military is cooperating,''
Aventajado said.
</P>
<P>
   Skirmishes between the rebels and troops, changes in the
government negotiating team, and the need for security arrangements
on the island of Jolo have delayed formal talks, although the
rebels have discussed their goals informally with government
envoys.
</P>
<P>
   Three Germans, two French, two Finns, two South Africans, a
Lebanese, nine Malaysians and two Filipinos were kidnapped from a
Malaysian diving resort April 23 and taken to the island of Jolo.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf, the smaller and more radical of two guerrilla
groups fighting for an independent Islamic state in the
impoverished southern Philippines, brought world attention to a
rebellion that has simmered for decades when they kidnapped the 21
tourists and resort employees.
</P>
<P>
   It is part of a wave of recent violence in the southern
Philippines triggered by fighting between Muslim rebels and
government troops that has displaced more than 200,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting has been limited to the southern Mindanao region,
home of the mostly Roman Catholic Philippines' Muslim minority, but
several bombs have struck the capital of Manila since the rebels
threatened to target cities.
</P>
<P>
   While the Abu Sayyaf espouse political ideals, many say they are
bandits who survive by kidnapping and extortion.
</P>
<P>
   Informally, the Abu Sayyaf have asked for as much as $2 million
just to free an ill German hostage, Renate Wallert.
</P>
<P>
   Their formal demands so far include creation of an independent
Islamic state -- something President Joseph Estrada has repeatedly
refused to consider.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's talks are likely to open in the township of Patikul
with the Abu Sayyaf's political demands, negotiator Farouk Hussein
said Thursday. There have been no demands for money in the last two
informal meetings with rebel leaders, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A government doctor, along with envoys from the negotiators and
several journalists, visited the camp of about 150 guerrillas
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese hostage Marie Moarbes sent a message to her family
through the TV journalists: ''Thanks Mom, I love you. Please pray
for our quick release. It's been very hard. Please tell Papa I hope
I'll see him very soon. Everybody is suffering here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
