<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Lets Syria Know of New Rules  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA KING
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- The bulldozed earth and jagged half-built
fences of Israel's northern frontier mark the battlefront in a
high-stakes new war of nerves -- with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's precipitous pullout from a swath of south Lebanon it
had occupied for nearly two decades has altered the strategic
landscape as well as the physical one, placing Syria, the power
broker in Lebanon, squarely in Israel's gun sights if there is
trouble along the raw new Lebanese frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Up and down Israel's political and military chain of command,
the warnings to Syria are being repeated: Now that Israeli troops
are out of Lebanon, the ground rules have changed.
</P>
<P>
   From here on out, the message goes, if Syria is seen as
inspiring attacks against Israel -- whether by Shiite Muslim
guerrillas, or rejectionist Palestinians in Lebanon, or others -- it
will pay the price.
</P>
<P>
   ''Israel's presence in Lebanon tied its hands to some extent,''
Prime Minister Ehud Barak told a special parliamentary session in
the border town of Kiryat Shemona on Thursday. ''But from now on,
there are no limits on a tough Israeli response to all aggression
against it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the event of any attack, the 30,000 Syrian troops stationed
in Lebanon -- enforcers of Syria's near-total power there -- would be
a prime target for Israeli reprisals, said Lt. Gen. Shaul Mofaz,
Israel's army chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   ''The planes are ready, and the pilots are on call,'' he said,
hours after Israel's Lebanon pullout was completed at daybreak
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Barak told lawmakers Thursday that any cross-border attacks
would be viewed as an act of war, and no ''target or player in
Lebanon'' -- taken to mean Syria -- would be immune from retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   Such rhetoric might seem like an about-face for Barak, the
Israeli leader who has most fervently sought peace with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister spent his first five months in office wooing
Syrian President Hafez Assad to the bargaining table, sometimes
startling Israelis with his warm words about the Syrian leader.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak clearly believes that a drastic deterrent is the only
certain way to stave off confrontation in this volatile
post-pullout phase -- and thus keep alive hopes for restarting the
talks with Syria, which broke down in January.
</P>
<P>
   Preemptively, however, Israel has sought to diplomatically
justify strikes against Syrian targets in retaliation for any
attacks launched from Lebanese soil.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the pullout from Lebanon, Barak wrote to U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan and other world leaders, accusing
Syria of fomenting violence by using Hezbollah and Palestinian
radicals.
</P>
<P>
   Besides trying to marshal world support, Barak made an unusual
direct appeal to Lebanon not to let Syria or others use it as a
springboard for attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do not allow again terror organizations and extremists ... to
kindle a fire on Lebanon's back for the sake of interests that are
not yours,'' he said in his speech to lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Outwardly, Syria is expressing delight over Israel's pullout,
with its state-run media proclaiming a great victory for the
Lebanese guerrillas. But the withdrawal casts an uncomfortable
spotlight on Syria's own occupation of Lebanon, which is deeply
resented by most Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
   The last Israeli tanks had barely rolled back across the border
when the Clinton administration repeated its assertion -- now aimed
solely at Syria -- that foreign forces should leave Lebanon, and
U.N. peacekeepers should help the Lebanese government keep order in
the border zone.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is Israel's most implacable foe, Syria has kept its
own border with Israel calm since the 1973 war. Few in Israel
believe, however, that such quiet can be taken for granted any time
soon along the Lebanese frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers patrolling the border have been told to hold their fire
unless their lives are in danger, because any flare-up could
quickly become a larger conflagration.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is well aware that whatever international approval it
enjoys for having gotten out of Lebanon would quickly evaporate if
it is seen as overreacting to a cross-border clash.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, failing to respond to provocation could cost
it crucial credibility, opening the way to an endless succession of
Syrian-sponsored guerrilla strikes against Israel's northern
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ''You must simply understand that we are facing a new reality,''
Mofaz told his troops. ''It has changed overnight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
