<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 92; Nasdaq Up 58  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today as jittery investors
once again moved money from one sector to another. Technology
stocks rose, buoying the Nasdaq, but financial shares stumbled.
</P>
<P>
   In midafternoon trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite
index was up 57.62 to 3,328.23.
</P>
<P>
   Other stock indicators were mixed. The Dow Jones industrial
average was down 91.50 at 10,443.85, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 1.04 at 1,400.09.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks continued a rebound that began Wednesday as
investors started channeling money into stocks that have tumbled in
the past few weeks. Cisco Systems was up 2 5/16 at 57 7/16, and
Oracle rose 5[ to 69].
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a better feel to the tech sector today,'' said Barry
Hyman, senior equity analyst at Ehrenkrantz King Nussbaum in New
York. ''Improved volume is an excellent sign, as is Cisco's ability
to hit a bottom and recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were also heartened by the Nasdaq's ability to bounce
back even without Microsoft. Its shares fell 3\ to 62 5/16 a day
after a federal judge ordered the Justice Department to revise its
plan to break up the world's leading computer software maker and
submit the new version by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The order renewed expectations that Microsoft will be split into
two, or even three, parts. Goldman Sachs analyst Rick Sherlund told
clients a broken-up Microsoft would undoubtedly would be worth less
than a whole one.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts fear the sector's recovery may be fragile,
because the interest rate worries that undermined technology stocks
in the first place are still haunting the market. Most market
watchers anticipate choppy trading for at least another week, with
no clear leadership from any one sector.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to follow through,'' Hyman said. ''If we don't, a
single up day is meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, bank stocks that have thrived lately were mostly lower.
Citigroup fell 1~ to 59{ after Morgan Stanley Dean Witter cut its
rating on the stock to ''outperform'' from ''strong buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Bank of New York fell 1 to 47.
</P>
<P>
   The market was little affected by the Commerce Department's
report that the U.S. economy, powered by brisk consumer and
government spending, grew at a robust 5.4 percent annual rate
during the first three months of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation-wary investors were most interested in an inflation
gauge tied to the gross domestic product, which rose at an annual
rate of 3.1 percent in the first quarter. The market had
anticipated a slightly bigger increase. Surging energy prices
accounted for most of the gain.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues were marginally ahead of decliners on the New
York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 625.51 million shares,
well behind Wednesday's brisk pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 5.69 to 467.43.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
