<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sheldon Silver is not out of the woods yet  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Sheldon Silver's speakership in the New York
state Assembly survived a frontal assault this week.
</P>
<P>
   But his victory over Democratic dissidents led by his former
majority leader, Michael Bragman, does not mean Silver has
necessarily won the war.
</P>
<P>
   Silver rallied 77 other Democrats around him to stave off the
challenge for his job. Bragman, who needed 50 votes among the 98
Democrats in the Assembly to take over as speaker, got only 18
other Democrats to vote with him on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Silver criticized people who would focus on the
one-fifth or so of the Democratic delegation willing to stand
publicly against him. What about the four-fifths who were with him,
he asked?
</P>
<P>
   ''Eighty percent said they were happy,'' he declared. ''That's
what happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been that a great many of the 80 percent were merely
saying they were not unhappy enough with Silver to change speakers.
At this time.
</P>
<P>
   The distinction is crucial to Silver's future as speaker, and it
is one that will not become better defined until -- or if -- he is
formally re-elected to a new two-year term as speaker prior to the
start of the 2001 legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   Silver said that assuming he wins re-election to another term in
the Assembly from his Manhattan district, he wants to continue
being speaker. In this job he is the most powerful Democrat in New
York state government, with great influence on a $78 billion state
budget and virtual veto power over bills in the New York state
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ''The past six years have been the greatest six years of my
life,'' Silver said of his speakership.
</P>
<P>
   In arguing against Silver's removal as speaker, many Democrats
praised the job he has done negotiating for health care, public
schools, higher education and other social programs with a
sometimes-hostile Republican Gov. George Pataki and state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But many also argued that late May, in the last month of a
legislative session and in the middle of an election year, is a
lousy time to change speakers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why now?'' asked Assemblyman Herman Farrell, a Manhattan
Democrat close to Silver. ''Why at this time? Why in this manner?''
</P>
<P>
   Farrell added, ''The speaker issue is an issue that should be in
December this year -- if it's a real issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not the time,'' Assemblyman Roger Green of Brooklyn
said on the floor of the Assembly. ''You know it's not the place.
Our place is in a Democratic conference.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the words of praise Silver heard as Democrats beat back
Bragman's uprising, there was also the lingering sentiment that
timing -- not Silver's own performance -- was a key consideration in
many people's minds as to why he should be retained.
</P>
<P>
   But what about November? December? That question was not
answered this week, and it will continue to hang over Silver and
his regime through the rest of this legislative session and the
fall presidential, U.S. senatorial and legislative elections. It
will not be resolved for sure until Democrats elect a speaker for a
new two-year term.
</P>
<P>
   The other unanswerable question was how many of Silver's
Democrats were really dissatisfied enough with his leadership to
cast him aside.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said he counted 53 at one point last week and another
eight or nine who would have been on his side had he demonstrated
enough support to topple Silver. But they evaporated as Silver
twisted arms and threatened members' political existences, Bragman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Silver scoffed at those numbers and denied coercing anyone to
stay in his corner.
</P>
<P>
   But it is clear that once the smoke cleared, Bragman did get 18
other Democrats to stand up publicly and criticize a sitting
speaker who holds the power of their political life or death over
their heads. That alone was remarkable in the memories of anyone
now at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The ball is undoubtedly now in Silver's court.
</P>
<P>
   While saying little about addressing calls for reform raised by
Bragman's dissidents as well as some of the members who stayed with
him, Silver did announce plans to form a committee to recommend
changes in how the Democrats run the house. Whether the complaints
by both dissidents and some members standing by Silver -- excessive
staff influence on the affairs of the Assembly, the extreme
difficulty in seeing Silver personally -- would be addressed
substantively was an open question.
</P>
<P>
   Silver was also said to be trying hard to put a face on his
sincerity to mend fences by meeting face-to-face with Democratic
members.
</P>
<P>
   Silver stamped out what ended up being a brush fire. The bonfire
is what he is now concerned with.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Joel Stashenko is Capitol Editor for The Associated Press in
Albany. He can be reached at P.O. Box 7165, Capitol Station,
Albany, N.Y., 12224.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
