<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton says she understands skepticism about her run  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton said Thursday she
understands why some people are skeptical about her intentions in
running for the U.S. Senate, but would not use the seat as a
stepping stone to run for president in 2004, even if party leaders
ask her to.
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging ''Voice of the Voter'' forum in which she
faced questions about everything from where she expected to spend
eternity to the appropriateness of linking new Senate rival Rick
Lazio to former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, the first lady said,
''I feel I owe it to the people of New York to serve a six-year
term.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, for the first time, Clinton said she understood
''there are skeptics. I don't blame people for being skeptical.''
</P>
<P>
   ''People will have to judge me and draw whatever conclusions
they want ... I'm committed to serving my six-year term,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed on what she would do if Democrats pleaded with her to
run in 2004 if they lost the White House this year, she said:
''That is not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have repeatedly charged that the first lady wants to
use the Senate as a stepping stone for a presidential run, if not
in 2004, then in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   During the forum, attended by about 85 Rochester-area residents,
Clinton said that while she wouldn't personally try to link Lazio
to Gingrich, ''I cannot speak for all my supporters because
certainly the facts are that he was closely allied during those
years ... with that leadership in the Congress, and I think New
Yorkers need to know that.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, campaign aides to the first lady have already been
bashing the Long Island congressman as a Gingrich lieutenant who
embraced the former speaker's ''Contract with America.'' Lazio, who
stepped into the race last Friday after New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani bowed out, has said he supported only those parts of the
contract he felt were good for New York such as lower taxes and a
balanced budget.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by one self-described conservative at the forum about how
she could work in the Senate given that she is such a polarizing
figure, Clinton said she has already shown she can work with people
in Congress who don't particularly like her. She cited her work
last year with Texas' Tom Delay -- ''someone who has never said a
good word in public about me or my husband'' -- on legislation
dealing with children aging out of foster care.
</P>
<P>
   ''The important thing in the Senate is not ever to be insulted
by whatever anybody says about you ... (and) after what I've been
through for the last seven years, nothing they can say can possibly
hurt my feelings,'' she said to laughter from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   The questioners in the 1{-hour forum were part of a voter
awareness project sponsored by Rochester's WXXI Public
Broadcasting, WOKR-TV and the Rochester Democrat &AMP; Chronicle. The
questions were selected at random.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the first lady was asked by a Republican: ''If you
were to die tonight, would you know if you would spend eternity in
heaven or hell?''
</P>
<P>
   Momentarily taken aback, Clinton finally responded: ''I consider
myself a person of faith. I consider myself like any person of
faith to be doing the very best I can.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope that I will be someone who will live a life that is
worthy of my strong Methodism and my Christian faith and my
commitment to doing the very best I can as a human being to live up
to the example of our Lord and savior,'' she added. ''But I cannot
tell you where I will be. I can only hope and pray that I will find
favor in God's eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   With the audience in silence, the first lady went on to say she
did not believe ''that we should be, in public life, be putting
people in a position of responding to questions that really focus
more on one's personal faith.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
