<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 189; Nasdaq Down 6  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Weakness in blue-chip stocks threatened to
deflate the Nasdaq's budding recovery today. Jittery investors once
again moved money from one sector to another, fleeing the financial
sector after an analyst raised concerns about profits.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the Dow
Jones industrial average was down 188.82 at 10,346.53, its low
point for the session.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was down 5.50 to 3,265.11. In earlier
trading, the index had risen as much as 115.23 as investors snapped
up stocks that have fallen steeply in recent sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Other stock indicators had also turned lower. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was down 12.20 at 1,386.85.
</P>
<P>
   Weakness in financial stocks undermined the market. Goldman
Sachs led a number of brokerage stocks lower after a Merrill Lynch
analyst said Goldman is likely to miss second-quarter earnings
estimates of $1.47 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerages have thrived in the past few quarters, pumped up by
heavy trading volume and a robust climate for initial public
offerings. But since the Nasdaq first tumbled from its March 10
peak, volume has slipped and the market for IPOs has dried up.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Goldman Sachs fell 5 11/16 to 74 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Dow component J.P. Morgan fell 4[ to 128{. Citigroup fell
2 9/16 to 58 13/16 after Morgan Stanley Dean Witter cut its rating
on the stock to ''outperform'' from ''strong buy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow was also hurt by Microsoft, which fell 3~ to 61 11/16.
On Wednesday, a day after a federal judge ordered the Justice
Department to revise its plan to break up the world's leading
computer software maker and submit the new version by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The order renewed expectations that Microsoft will be split into
two, or even three, parts. Goldman Sachs analyst Rick Sherlund told
clients a broken-up Microsoft would undoubtedly would be worth less
than a whole one.
</P>
<P>
   Without Microsoft, technology stocks proved unable to continue a
rebound that began Wednesday as investors started channeling money
into stocks that have tumbled in the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were warning that any attempts to rally may be fragile,
because the interest rate worries that undermined technology stocks
in the first place are still haunting the market. Most market
watchers anticipate choppy trading for at least another week, with
no clear leadership from any one sector.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to follow through (on rallies),'' said Barry Hyman,
senior equity analyst at Ehrenkrantz King Nussbaum in New York.
''If we don't, a single up day is meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   The market was little affected by the Commerce Department's
report that the U.S. economy, powered by brisk consumer and
government spending, grew at a robust 5.4 percent annual rate
during the first three months of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation-wary investors were most interested in an inflation
gauge tied to the gross domestic product, which rose at an annual
rate of 3.1 percent in the first quarter. The market had
anticipated a slightly bigger increase. Surging energy prices
accounted for most of the gain.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues overtook advancers by a 7-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 752.26 million
shares, well behind Wednesday's brisk pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.60 to 462.34.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
