<HEADLINE> Prosecutor Selected for Lee Trial  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A veteran federal prosecutor of organized
crime and public corruption cases was selected Thursday to lead the
government's trial team against fired Los Alamos National
Laboratory scientist Wen Ho Lee.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department announced that George A. Stamboulidis,
now in the U.S. Attorney's Office in New York's borough of
Brooklyn, will take over as chief prosecutor Tuesday. The trial is
set to begin Nov. 6 in Albuquerque, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Last Dec. 10, Lee was charged with 59 counts of breaching lab
security. The prosecution contends Lee transferred 19 files from
secure to unsecured computers and downloaded some material to
computer tapes. Prosecutors have said the material included the top
secret ''crown jewels'' of American nuclear science.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lee, who was a nuclear physicist in the weapons section
of the lab, has not been charged with espionage, prosecutors
contend he intended to aid a foreign government.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials, requesting anonymity, have said he may have
planned to use the material to get a job in China or Taiwan if he
were laid off at Los Alamos, which was considering staff reductions
at the time he acted.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 60, could get life in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Stamboulidis, now chief of Long Island offices for the U.S.
Attorney for the Eastern District of New York, won convictions
during the 1990s against notorious crime figures, including Vincent
Gigante, boss of the Genovese crime family, and more than two dozen
members of the Luchese, Colombo and Gambino crime families. He won
Justice Department awards in 1994, 1995 and 1999 for these
convictions.
</P>
<P>
   He also won convictions in prosecutions of public officials on
Long Island. Earlier this month, FBI Director Louis J. Freeh
commended him for convicting more than two dozen people in a
racketeering enterprise involving truck theft rings and extortion
by political party officials.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the Justice Department in 1988 after clerking for U.S.
District Judge Louis Bechtle in Philadelphia. Born in Alabama,
Stamboulidis was graduated with honors from the State University of
New York-Stony Brook and Temple University School of Law.
</P>
<P>
   He replaces Bob Gorence, the assistant U.S. attorney who
directed the high-profile investigation. Gorence remains on the
trial team.
</P>
<P>
   Until March, Gorence had been the top-ranking career prosecutor
in the Albuquerque U.S. attorney's office. He took charge of the
Lee case in April 1999.
</P>
<P>
   It is not uncommon for the Justice Department to bring in a
veteran outside prosecutor for high-profile cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
