<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Satisfied With Explanation  </HEADLINE>
By CANDICE HUGHES
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLORENCE, Italy (AP) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said Thursday that she is ''satisfied'' with Russia's
explanation for the warm welcome Moscow gave a Yugoslav general
indicted for war crimes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov's sharp criticism of the
U.N. tribunal that indicted the general was another matter.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is doing what it has to do in a very difficult situation,''
Albright said at the end of a two-day NATO foreign ministers
meeting. ''I disagree with the foreign minister's assessment. I
very much support what the war crimes tribunal is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   As a permanent member of the U.N. Security Council, Russia voted
to create the tribunal, based in The Hague, Netherlands, Albright
noted.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it is doing what we asked it to do,'' she said of the
tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. resolutions require Russia to arrest war crimes suspects on
its soil. Instead, the Yugoslav defense minister, Gen. Dragoljub
Ojdanic, was a guest of the Russian Defense Ministry for five days
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   When the NATO foreign ministers demanded an explanation, Ivanov
blamed a ''technical hitch'' and said Wednesday that ''measures''
were being taken to see that it wouldn't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm satisfied with his explanation,'' Albright said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Ojdanic, like Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, has been
indicted by the war crimes tribunal on charges of war crimes in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov's presence at the Florence meeting, which included a
session of the NATO-Russia Permanent Joint Council, marked Russia's
return to the NATO table after a yearlong hiatus provoked by the
alliance's air war against Yugoslavia over Kosovo. Moscow, which
bitterly opposed the NATO campaign, had suspended relations with
NATO on all but Balkans-related issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Permanent Joint Council was created in 1997 to provide a
forum for NATO-Russia consultations and ease their concerns about
enlargement of the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, NATO also welcomed Croatia as the 27th member of
the Partnership for Peace program, which allows the Zagreb
government to participate in many of NATO's activities without
being a member of the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   It was a big step on the road to democracy for the former
Yugoslav republic, which is just emerging from nine years under the
rule of the late President Franjo Tudjman.
</P>
<P>
   ''Croatia's new leaders deserve enormous credit for the steps
they have taken to bring their land closer to Europe's democratic
mainstream, and away from the extreme nationalism that has
sometimes plagued southeastern Europe,'' Albright said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-25-00 1547 </TRAILER>
