<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oral Diseases Epidemic Among Poor  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN GULLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Most Americans have healthier teeth than their
grandparents thanks to better dental care, but a ''silent
epidemic'' of oral diseases, from cavities to cancer, afflicts the
poor and minorities because of economic and social barriers to
getting care, the surgeon general says.
</P>
<P>
   David Satcher, the nation's top doctor, said Thursday that a new
report -- the government's first-ever comprehensive look at oral
health in America -- shows that Americans' teeth and mouths are in
the best shape ever. Yet ''profound disparities'' in oral health
exist, with many poor people and racial groups having untreated
oral diseases, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We still have a problem,'' Satcher said at a news conference.
''Not all Americans are achieving better oral health.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans middle-aged or younger can expect to keep their
teeth for life, thanks to regular visits to the dentists, treating
cavities with fillings, drinking fluoridated water, smoking less
and having a better diet, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   But many poor people and minorities cannot afford to see
dentists and either cannot or do not make lifestyle changes that
would lower their risk of having oral diseases and tooth loss.
</P>
<P>
   While problems like tooth decay and cavities affect nearly
everyone, poor minorities are hit harder, said the report, an
amalgamation of clinical and epidemiological studies.
</P>
<P>
   One study cited in the report showed that nearly half of all
poor blacks and Hispanics had untreated tooth decay. By contrast,
about one-third of all Americans have untreated decay.
</P>
<P>
   Oral problems begin early: More than a third of low-income
children have at least one untreated decayed tooth by the time they
are 9 years old, compared with 17 percent of children living above
the poverty line, the study showed.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity grows as children get older. Over 43 percent of
poor children have tooth decay by age 17 compared with 23 percent
of youngsters who are better off, the study showed.
</P>
<P>
   Tooth problems often go unchecked because children lack
insurance coverage. Uninsured children are 2{ times less likely to
get dental checkups compared with children who have insurance,
Satcher noted.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 108 million Americans, including 26 million
children, have no insurance coverage for dental care.
</P>
<P>
   Even poor children who have dental insurance are not getting the
care they need, the report said. The government estimates that 80
percent of Medicaid eligible youngsters do not receive dental care
because few dentists take Medicaid patients and dental care is not
a priority for poor families.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have a card but no care,'' said Burton Edelstein, a
pediatric dentist and director of the Children's' Dental Health
Project in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   American Dental Association officials said dentists have a good
track record for providing free and discounted care to needy
people, but said government needs to do more.
</P>
<P>
   ''State and federal agencies must step up to the plate to help
the dental profession deliver care to the maximum number of
Americans, in a sense by putting their money where the nation's
mouth is,'' said Richard F. Mascola, ADA president.
</P>
<P>
   The report also faulted communities for not having fluoridated
water -- which can prevent tooth decay. Some 144 million people
receive fluoridated water from public supplies. But with several
cities lacking fluoridated water -- the report cites San Diego,
Portland, Ore., Tucson, Ariz., and San Jose, Calif., among them --
over 100 million Americans do not benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The report calls for more screening for oral cancers and more
studies of dental health disparities, as well as anti-smoking and
water fluoridation projects in communities that don't have them.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, it urges Americans to brush and floss daily.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Surgeon General's report:
http://www.nidcr.nih.gov/sgr/sgr.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-25-00 1552 </TRAILER>
