<DOCNO> APW20000525.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Without comment Senate unanimously approves Supreme Court nominee  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The Senate Thursday unanimously approved a
former attorney general to become Gov. Christie Whitman's sixth
nominee to the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat James R. Zazzali of Rumson was confirmed in a 25-0
vote. He replaces Associate Justice Daniel O'Hern, who reached the
mandatory retirement age of 70 on May 23.
</P>
<P>
   Zazzali will join Chief Justice Deborah Poritz and Associate
Justice Peter G. Verniero, all former attorneys general nominated
by Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   An assistant prosecutor when former Gov. Brendan Byrne was the
Essex County prosecutor, Byrne later named Zazzali his attorney
general.
</P>
<P>
   Zazzali was not present Thursday for the Senate vote. Lawmakers
approved the nomination without a word of comment from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Zazzali faced only brief questioning from senators earlier this
week at a committee hearing on issues, including the role of the
judiciary and the needs of the court system.
</P>
<P>
   ''I keenly believe the Legislature is the voice of the people,
and the judges and the justices should recognize that,'' Zazzali
said.
</P>
<P>
   Zazzali served as attorney general for 10 months at the end of
former Gov. Byrne's term in 1981 and 1982. He also served as
general counsel to the New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority
under Byrne.
</P>
<P>
   Zazzali, who turns 63 on June 17, is the oldest person Whitman
has nominated. Although all Supreme Court justices must be
confirmed for lifetime tenure by the Senate after seven years, this
will not be an issue for Zazzali since he will hit mandatory
retirement in 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the chief justice, the six associate justices are
supposed to be evenly split, three Republicans and three Democrats.
Because O'Hern is a Democrat, tradition holds that he be replaced
with someone from the same party.
</P>
<P>
   Zazzali was a commissioner on the State Commission of
Investigation from 1984 to 1994, including a period as chairman.
The SCI is an independent office created by the Legislature to
examine and issue written reports on corruption and policy
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman last year named Zazzali to a search committee to find
candidates for state police superintendent. He also headed a
coalition of six former state attorneys general who supported
former Attorney General Peter Verniero's hotly contested nomination
to the high court.
</P>
<P>
   Zazzali, of Rumson, is a partner in the Newark law firm Zazzali,
Zazzali, Fagella &AMP; Nowak with his brother, Andrew Zazzali. He
graduated from Georgetown University in 1958 and earned a law
degree there in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's other appointments to the high court are associate
justices Virginia Long, Jaynee LaVecchia and James Coleman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
