<HEADLINE> Milosevic Cracks Down on Students  </HEADLINE>
By DUSAN STOJANOVIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Fearing a student uprising,
Yugoslavia ordered all universities Thursday to end the spring
semester a week early and banned campus gatherings across Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The students had called a major rally for Friday to protest a
government crackdown against critics, opponents and the independent
media.
</P>
<P>
   In an order signed by the Serbian education minister, all
universities in the dominant Yugoslav republic were ordered to
finish classes on Friday, a week early, the independent Beta news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   ''There must be no gatherings or manifestations'' on university
campuses after Friday, the decree said.
</P>
<P>
   The crackdown came after weeks of daily opposition protests
heavily supported by university students in Serbia's largest cities
against the government of President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Marija Bogdanovic, a former dean of Belgrade University and
dissident philosophy professor, said the move aimed at ''thwarting
the planned strike'' at the university.
</P>
<P>
   Although the order ended classes Friday, it allowed final exams
to be held as scheduled in June, but banned students from campus
libraries.
</P>
<P>
   ''With this decision, the Serbian universities have become
forbidden zones,'' said a statement by the opposition Democratic
Party of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ''This draconian decision has destroyed the autonomy of the
universities, and their deans were given a role to defend the
regime, instead of defending classes, students and the science,''
it said.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred university students held a brief protest in the
center of Belgrade, blocking traffic and pledging a massive turnout
for the protest on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In Nis, Serbia's third largest city, about 2,000 university
students marched toward the police station before being stopped by
police, who ordered them to disband.
</P>
<P>
   Later in Belgrade, about 2,000 people gathered for a rally for
the ninth straight day to protest the government takeover of the
capital's independent radio and television stations.
</P>
<P>
   With daily street protests continuing in Serbia's largest
cities, the government has accused the student group Otpor, or
Resistance, of treason and links with the Western powers that
bombed Yugoslavia for 78 days last spring.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, masked men attacked Belgrade University students in
a downtown building and broke up a sit-in protest.
</P>
<P>
   Protesting the attack, 15 professors of the Drama Arts faculty
announced Thursday they were going on strike and won't hold classes
or exams.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are serious indications that those who beat up students
are under the patronage of certain political parties,'' the
professors said in a statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
