<HEADLINE> Home Might Be Where Reno's Heart Is  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After seven stormy years here, Janet Reno
would rather return home to Florida than take a seat on the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Recently Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said at a news conference
he would like to see Reno on the high court.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about that at her weekly news conference Thursday, Reno
replied, ''I was touched that Senator Schumer said that, but I
think I want to go home.'' Reno, who will turn 62 on July 21, has
joked for some time that she would like to travel cross-country in
a camper after leaving office.
</P>
<P>
   The second-longest-serving attorney general in U.S. history,
Reno took office in 1993 after 15 years as an elected state
prosecutor in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with a deadly FBI tear gas assault on a religious
compound near Waco, Texas, during her first month, Reno has been
immersed for almost her entire tenure in controversial cases,
including the long-running campaign finance investigation and, most
recently, the Elian Gonzalez affair.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general who held the job the longest, William Wirt,
served from 1817 into 1829 under Presidents James Monroe and John
Q. Adams.
</P>
</TEXT>
