<HEADLINE> Ex-INS Espionage Case Goes to Jury  </HEADLINE>
By MEG RICHARDS
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- A jury began deliberating Thursday in the case of a
senior U.S. immigration official accused of espionage for passing
secret information to a friend who had contacts in the Cuban
government.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Mariano Faget, 54, went to the jury after a
federal prosecutor called Mariano ''a government employee willing
to betray the trust of people he was sworn to serve,'' while the
defense called him ''an honest government servant who made a
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Faget, a naturalized U.S. citizen from Cuba, could get 10 years
in prison if convicted of charges including violating the Espionage
Act.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Curtis Miner told the jury that investigators set a
trap for Faget to see what he would do with classified information:
They planted a phony story that a certain Cuban offficial planned
to defect.
</P>
<P>
   Faget was almost immediately caught on tape telling his friend
and business partner Pedro Font over the phone about the impending
defection. At the time, Font was about to meet with a Cuban
diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   Faget testified that he tipped off his friend because he feared
Font would be harmed if Cuban officials thought Font was involved
with the defection.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Edward O'Donnell told the jury: ''This is an
honest government servant who made a mistake, but he did not
violate the law. ''It was never his intent to hurt this country ...
his intent was to warn his friend.''
</P>
<P>
   But the prosecutor ridiculed Faget's assertion that he didn't
think telling Font about the defection would hurt national
security.
</P>
<P>
   ''He took it out of the realm of control of the United States
government and gave it to someone else, to use however they
wanted,'' Miner said.
</P>
<P>
   Faget was close to retirement after 34 years with the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
