<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Critics Say Snowmobile Ban 'Crazy'  </HEADLINE>
By MATT KELLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional critics attacked the National
Park Service plan to ban snowmobiles from most parks, calling the
move an unjustified attempt to please environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   ''It really is crazy what they're trying to do here,'' Rep.
Collin Peterson, D-Minn., said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The park service announced last month it was banning nearly all
snowmobile traffic in 25 national parks, recreation areas and other
agency lands. Conservationists estimated about 180,000 snowmobilers
used park service land last year.
</P>
<P>
   Separate hearings before House Resources and Senate Natural
Resources subcommittees gave snowmobilers a chance to vent their
anger and lawmakers a chance to grill the Interior Department
official who announced the ban.
</P>
<P>
   That official, Assistant Interior Secretary Donald Barry, stood
his ground. Barry said the ban merely enforces regulations the Park
Service had not been following and will protect federal land from
pollution and other damage.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not about closure of national parks to the American
public. This is about restricting a form of access to national
parks,'' Barry said. He compared the ban to rules preventing
motorcyclists from riding up the steps of the Lincoln Memorial in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Twomey, president of snowmobile-maker Arctic Cat, said
Barry maligned the industry last month when he called snowmobiles
''noisy, antiquated machines that are no longer welcome in our
national parks.'' Twomey said manufacturers have been making
cleaner, quieter machines in response to customer demands.
</P>
<P>
   Twomey said the snowmobile business generates $6 billion a year
and is responsible for 65,000 jobs, including 10,000 in snowmobile
manufacturing. Surveys show snowmobilers are mostly middle-class
families who enjoy the outdoors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're mad because our access has now been denied to our
national parks,'' added Bill Manson of the American Council of
Snowmobile Associations. ''Mr. Barry has painted us to be an
antiquated bunch of wild people.''
</P>
<P>
   The ban does not apply to parks in Alaska and Voyageurs National
Park in Minnesota because Congress specifically allowed snowmobile
use in those parks. It also does not apply to the Yellowstone and
Grand Teton parks in northwestern Wyoming because the park service
is considering a separate ban for them.
</P>
<P>
   The snowmobile ban is one of a series of moves by federal land
management agencies to restrict motorized traffic in national
parks. In March, new restrictions were outlined to limit the use of
Jet Skis and similar motorized watercraft in some parks. Efforts
are under way to limit private automobile traffic to reduce
congestion and air pollution at some of the busiest parks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-25-00 1740 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000525.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former E. German Police Chief Dies  </HEADLINE>
By TONY CZUCZKA
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Erich Mielke, who headed former communist East
Germany's dreaded secret police and spy agency for three decades,
has died at 92, a Berlin city official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Berliner Kurier, in a report to appear in its
Friday edition, said Mielke died Monday at a Berlin home for the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   An official at the Berlin registrar's office confirmed that
Mielke's death had been reported to the agency, but he could not
say when he died. The official, who spoke by telephone, refused to
give his name.
</P>
<P>
   Mielke, one of the most hated men in East Germany, headed the
Ministry of State Security, known as the Stasi, that snooped on
citizens to suppress dissent against the communist regime and
placed thousands of agents abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The all-pervasive network included 85,000 full-time domestic
spies and 170,000 voluntary informers. The Stasi archive kept tabs
on several million people.
</P>
<P>
   Once the regime's No. 2 man, the ailing Mielke had recently
lived a secluded life in eastern Berlin, reportedly on a monthly
pension of about $465.
</P>
<P>
   A lifelong communist who fled Germany in the 1930s to escape the
Nazis, Mielke was jailed shortly after the collapse of East Germany
and unification in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   A Berlin court convicted him in 1993 for involvement as a young
communist street fighter in the murders of two Berlin policemen on
Aug. 9, 1931. He was released in 1995 after serving two-thirds of
his six-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   But he escaped prosecution for his 1957-89 leadership of the
Stasi, including charges related to shooting deaths at the Berlin
Wall, because of poor health and senility.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Berlin on Dec. 28, 1907, Mielke joined a communist youth
group in 1921. He became a full member in 1925 and worked as a
reporter for the party's newspaper, ''Red Flag.''
</P>
<P>
   He became a member of the party's paramilitary force, leading to
his participation in the August 1931 demonstration in Berlin during
which the two policemen were shot and killed.
</P>
<P>
   Wanted for the killings, Mielke escaped to Belgium using
identification from the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Mielke went on to the Soviet Union and attended the elite
International Lenin School in Moscow in the mid-1930s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1936, he served in the International Brigade that fought in
the Spanish Civil War against Gen. Francisco Franco, whose forces
triumphed and set up a fascist dictatorship. Mielke was interned
for a time in France, along with other brigade members.
</P>
<P>
   In 1940, Mielke returned to the Soviet Union and then to
Soviet-occupied eastern Germany in 1945. He helped organize police
in the Soviet-occupied zone and became deputy chief of state
security when East Germany was founded in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   He took over as minister in 1957, a post he held until the
Stalinist regime collapsed at the time the Berlin Wall fell in
November 1989. Stasi offices across East Germany were stormed by
citizens during the peaceful democratic revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Mielke went on trial for shootings at the Wall along with East
Germany's last Stalinist leader, Erich Honecker, in 1992. But he
was dropped from the case because he was also on trial for the
police slayings, and was later declared too senile to follow the
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Honecker was also dropped for reasons of health and died in
exile in Chile of liver cancer in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Mielke resided with his wife in eastern Berlin until March, when
he was admitted to a home for the elderly where his son works as a
medic. His wife, Gertrude, reportedly could no longer care for her
badly disabled husband.
</P>
<P>
   Berliner Kurier reported that Mielke was to be buried June 10 at
an eastern Berlin cemetery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-25-00 1743 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000525.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defense begins presenting its case in Peeler trial  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- Lawyers for the man accused of ordering
the murder of 8-year-old Leroy ''B.J.'' Brown Jr. and his mother
began his defense Thursday by attempting to cast doubt on the
prosecution's timeline for the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Peeler is charged with capital felony. He's accused of
having his brother Adrian kill B.J. and Karen Clarke, to stop the
boy from testifying against Russell in a 1998 murder. B.J. was
expected to be a key witness in Peeler's trial in the barber shop
slaying of Clarke's boyfriend, Rudolph Snead Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The boy and his mother were gunned down in their Bridgeport home
on Jan. 7, 1999, several months before Peeler's trial in the Snead
killing was to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contend that they were killed at or just before 6
p.m. as they returned home from grocery shopping.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, Peeler's defense lawyers called a neighbor who
said he heard gunshots between 6:20 p.m. and 6:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Riley, a retired Norwalk police officer who lived around
the corner from Clarke and her son, said he was walking down his
driveway when he heard five or six gunshots. The first two shots,
he said, were very loud and clear, and sounded like they were
outside. Riley said after a four or five-second pause, he heard
three more shots. These shots were muffled and sounded like they
came from inside a house or car, Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   Riley said he did not call the police to report the shots. The
next day, after the bodies were discovered, Riley said he relayed
what he had heard to a female police officer he saw near the crime
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Jonathan Benedict tried to show that Riley was not
sure of the time he heard the shots.
</P>
<P>
   ''Would it be fair to say you can't give us an exact time?''
Benedict asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes,'' replied Riley.
</P>
<P>
   A precise timeline is important to prosecutors because they
claim Adrian Peeler left the murder scene and arrived at the
Comfort Inn in Milford sometime between 6:15 p.m. and 6:35 p.m. A
police officer testified earlier that it takes about 15 minutes to
drive from the murder scene to the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   If the murders were committed later, as the defense maintains,
that would mean Adrian Peeler would not have had time to do the
killings, then drive to the hotel and arrive by 6:35 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is scheduled to resume Tuesday. The defense plans to
call at least another four witnesses before wrapping up its case.
</P>
<P>
   Judge G. Sarsfield Ford said he expects the lawyers to give
closing arguments Wednesday. Deliberations are expected to begin
Friday after the judge instructs the jury on the law.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Peeler is to be tried once his brother's trial is
completed.
</P>
<P>
   Both brothers face the possibility of the death penalty if
convicted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-25-00 1755 </TRAILER>
