<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill on using census data to draw legislative districts delayed  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- After a plea for more time by Democrats,
the Assembly's ranking Republican postponed voting on a bill that
would force the state to use only the actual head count when
drawing legislative districts after the census this year.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans back the measure, but Democrats and other opponents
contend that method leaves out minorities, recent immigrants and
city residents from census figures.
</P>
<P>
   The bill cleared the Assembly's State Government Committee
Monday by a 3-2 vote along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Assembly Democratic Leader Joseph V. Doria Jr.,
D-Hudson, asked for more time.
</P>
<P>
   ''When the minority leader speaks, I listen. That bill will not
be voted on today,'' said Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, R-Salem.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he agreed with Doria that residents and legislators
need time to digest the census data when it is produced.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're willing to do that for a while,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   In asking for the delay, Doria said the public is just becoming
aware of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''Shouldn't we let this process of public opinion fully unfold
before rushing this bill on the Assembly floor? Shouldn't this be a
time to slow down the process,'' Doria said.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker would not say when a vote would be rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure it will be done soon, but not today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Apportionment Commission is required to use the
numbers from the U.S. Census Bureau to draw district boundaries for
state and federal representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Census Bureau will give the state two results. One will
be the actual head count of residents who answered the census. The
other is an estimate based on that data and statistical models.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has ruled that sampling-enhanced numbers
cannot be used in deciding the number of congressional
representatives from each state. Left unspecified was whether
sample-adjusted numbers could be used to allocate federal funds or
to draw boundaries for congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   States will have the option of using either adjusted or raw
census data to redraw the congressional and state legislative
district boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Bill sponsor, Assemblyman Michael P. Carroll, R-Morris, says New
Jersey's small towns and cities make it easier for census workers
to actually count residents. Using estimates would force the
redistricting commission to guess where people are living, Carroll
said.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll and other supporters said the state would be free to use
estimates when applying for federal funding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-25-00 1805 </TRAILER>
