<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Down 211; Nasdaq Off 65  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Nervous investors turned against the financial
sector Thursday, sending shares in Wall Street's largest investment
firms sharply lower on fears that the stock market's continuing
weakness will hurt their profits.
</P>
<P>
   The decline ended a nascent recovery in the technology sector
and stifled hopes that Wednesday's rally signaled a reversal of the
pessimism that has driven the market lower in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 211.43 to close at
10,323.92.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fell 65.26 to 3,205.35. In earlier
trading, the index rose as much as 115.23 as investors went on a
brief bargain-hunting spree.
</P>
<P>
   Other stock indicators also fell. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
dropped 17.53 to 1,381.52.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks plummeted after a Merrill Lynch analyst said
Goldman Sachs is likely to miss second-quarter earnings estimates
of $1.47 per share. Merrill's Judah Kraushaar, who has long held
the less optimistic view of $1.36 a share, said guidance from
Goldman officials has convinced him that the firm will miss the
$1.47 target.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerages have thrived in the past few quarters, pumped up by
heavy trading volume and a robust climate for initial public
offerings. But since the Nasdaq first tumbled from its March 10
peak, volume has slipped and the market for IPOs has dried up.
</P>
<P>
   Kraushaar's warning reminded investors that the market's recent
weakness will indeed affect the profits of investment banks.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Goldman Sachs fell 7 to 73. Dow component J.P. Morgan
fell 3| to 129. Merrill Lynch fell 5 13/16 to 94 5/16 and Lehman
Brothers fell 5 3/16 to 72{.
</P>
<P>
   ''This shouldn't come as a surprise, especially in light of the
anemic volume we've been seeing,'' said Arthur Hogan, chief market
analyst at Jefferies &AMP; Co. ''But it's always someone's turn to go
to the woodshed, and the financials are the sector du jour.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow was also hurt by Microsoft, which fell 4 1/16 to 61{. On
Wednesday, a federal judge ordered the Justice Department to revise
its plan to break up the world's leading computer software maker
and submit the new version by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The order renewed expectations that Microsoft will be split into
two, or even three, parts. Goldman Sachs analyst Rick Sherlund told
clients a broken-up Microsoft would undoubtedly would be worth less
than the company as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Without Microsoft, technology stocks proved unable to continue a
rebound that began Wednesday as investors started channeling money
into stocks that have tumbled in the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks like Cisco, which were higher for much of the session,
ended modestly lower. Cisco fell | to 54{
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe that attempts to rally in the coming weeks may
be fragile, because the interest rate worries that undermined
technology stocks in the first place are still haunting the market.
Most market watchers anticipate choppy trading for at least another
week, with no clear leadership from any one sector.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to follow through (on rallies),'' said Barry Hyman,
senior equity analyst at Ehrenkrantz King Nussbaum in New York.
''If we don't, a single up day is meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   The market was little affected by the Commerce Department's
report that the U.S. economy, powered by brisk consumer and
government spending, grew at a robust 5.4 percent annual rate
during the first three months of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation-wary investors were most interested in an inflation
gauge tied to the gross domestic product, which rose at an annual
rate of 3.1 percent in the first quarter. The market had
anticipated a slightly bigger increase.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the report convinced no one on Wall Street that the
Federal Reserve has reached the end of its cycle of interest rate
increases.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first quarter is old news and will have no bearing on the
Fed's next move,'' said Bruce Steinberg, chief economist at Merrill
Lynch. Steinberg expects the Fed to raise interest rates at its
June meeting, and possibly once more after that.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where composite volume totaled 1.17
billion shares, compared with 1.37 billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   Volume is expected to taper off on Friday in advance of the
Memorial Day long weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 5.58 to 456.17.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1.3 percent.
Germany's Xetra DAX index rose 2.1 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100
gained 1.8 percent, and France's CAC-40 rose 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
