<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CIA Scolds 6 in Security Breach   </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Three current and three former senior CIA
officials, including former general counsel Michael O'Neill, have
been reprimanded or otherwise rebuked for their roles in an
investigation into former CIA Director John Deutch's home computer
security breaches, the CIA said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The actions against the six, administered this week by Air Force
Gen. John A. Gordon, the agency's deputy director, followed a
sharply critical report of the CIA's behavior by a presidential
advisory panel.
</P>
<P>
   The actions did not include a reprimand of CIA Director George
Tenet, who has also come under criticism, said CIA spokesman Bill
Harlow.
</P>
<P>
   However, Harlow said that Tenet recently met with President
Clinton on the matter. ''During that conversation, the director
acknowledged that he shared in the responsibility for shortcomings
identified in the report,'' Harlow said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Deutch has admitted violating security rules by processing
classified documents on several home computers that had Internet
access through an America Online account, one that was also used by
other family members.
</P>
<P>
   His laxness was discovered after he left the CIA in December
1996. However, no action was taken against him until last August
when Tenet stripped him of his security clearances.
</P>
<P>
   Both Deutch's conduct and the CIA's follow-up probe are being
reviewed by the Justice Department's Criminal Division.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's statement, the agency conceded that the Justice
Department and congressional oversight panels should have been
notified sooner, and that ''more aggressive damage control efforts,
such as the immediate removal of the unclassified computers used by
Mr. Deutch, should have been initiated.''
</P>
<P>
   The CIA statement said that three officials involved in the
follow-up investigation, including one still at the agency, were
''formally reprimanded in writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon ''formally admonished in writing'' two others, one of
them still at the agency; and ''orally admonished'' still another
who is still at the agency, the CIA said.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA declined to identify any of the six, citing ''reasons of
personal privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   But intelligence and congressional officials familiar with the
case who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said that O'Neil, the
former general counsel, and former Executive Director Nora Slatkin
were among those receiving formal written reprimands -- the sharpest
category of criticism of the six individuals involved.
</P>
<P>
   Also among those to receive either reprimands or admonishments,
the officials said, were the agency's former inspector general,
Frederick Hitz, and Richard Calder, currently the deputy director
for administration.
</P>
<P>
   The other two names could not be immediately determined.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Spaeder, O'Neil's lawyer, confirmed that his client had
received a written reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   ''We sincerely regret and vigorously disagree with General
Gordon's decision to reprimand Mr. O'Neil in connection with the
Deutch matter,'' Spaeder said. ''While working at the CIA, Mr.
O'Neil at all times conducted himself with the best interests of
the agency in mind and in complete good faith.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil declined to testify before the Senate Intelligence
Committee, citing Fifth Amendment protection against
self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil, a Washington lawyer, left the CIA in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A presidential advisory panel chaired by former Sen. Warren
Rudman, R-N.H., this month criticized the CIA's internal
investigation of security violations by Deutch, faulting Tenet in
particular as well as other high-ranking officials for failing to
aggressively pursue the case.
</P>
<P>
   The Rudman report was classified, but those familiar with it
said it followed conclusions of a CIA inspector general's report,
later declassified, which accused O'Neil and Slatkin of fumbling
and delaying the CIA's initial investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Both reports criticized the CIA for not reporting the home
computer security violations to the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Tenet removed himself from any further handling of the inquiry,
because of his own involvement, and turned matters over to Gordon,
the No. 2 man at the agency, to determine whether disciplinary
actions were warranted.
</P>
<P>
   The six reprimands-admonishments follow Gordon's inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Intelligence Committee Chairman Richard Shelby, R-Ala.,
who got a private briefing from Gordon this week, called the
reprimands ''a mild, if not weak, gesture.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that ''if anybody else had done this besides senior CIA
officials, they would have received much harsher punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his panel continues to investigate the matter, as does
the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of us on the committee are still troubled by the whole
episode, especially the large volume mishandled classified
documents,'' Shelby said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Harlow, the CIA spokesman, said the agency planned no further
disciplinary actions, although it had taken ''steps to strengthen
and clarify agency procedures'' to better safeguard computer files
and to make sure suspected violations are reported more quickly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
