<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman wants full power to control Camden  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Gov. Christie Whitman wants the power to
assume absolute control of Camden city government in her ''hip
pocket'' if the state's strict supervision of municipal finances
fails.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitman administration would need special legislation to
allow the full takeover. Officials have been preparing for that
since before the supervision began May 12.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reason that we're moving forward is not because I want the
state takeover, but because I'm afraid because of the past track
record, that without that authority in our hip pocket, that we
won't get that kind of cooperation we need out of some of the local
officials,'' Whitman said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a news conference, Whitman said she needs to have
the power available now instead of waiting to see if the state
management team says it is needed later.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really to have as a final tool to put this city on the
right track,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   Camden residents need to know that the state will do everything
it can to revitalize the city, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's also a level of expectation that I'm concerned about,
that the people of Camden have, that supervision allows them to do
more than it does allow them to do,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   State officials contend that Camden Mayor Milton Milan's
administration repeatedly ignored warnings to correct faulty
financial practices. The city does not keep proper records,
including a general ledger and an account of city payouts as
required by law, according to the state.
</P>
<P>
   On May 10, the state Local Finance Board gave state officials
the ability to approve all city spending, contracts and collective
bargaining agreements. State supervisors can limit debt, authorize
any refinancing and hire and fire non-Civil Service employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Division of Community Affairs started developing the
legislation as it began supervising city financial operations, said
Tom Damm, a spokesman for Commissioner Jane Kenny.
</P>
<P>
   ''Supervision is largely confined to financial matters. We are
pursuing legislation that would give us the tools to rehabilitate
the actual operations of government,'' Damm said.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, R-Salem, said he would probably
support a takeover.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the administration comes to me with a plan, then I think we
have to strongly consider it,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Donald T. DiFrancesco, R-Union, wants to review
what the governor is proposing before making any comment, said
spokeswoman Rae Hutton.
</P>
<P>
   Officials announced Tuesday that Sylvester Murray, a director at
Cleveland State University's urban public management program, will
act as an adviser to the state management team.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, a former city manager in San Diego, Ann Arbor, Mich.,
and Cincinnati, is an elected fellow with the National Academy of
Public Administrators, a Washington D.C., nonprofit group.
</P>
<P>
   The state will pay the organization up to $500,000 for six
months of advice.
</P>
<P>
   The first public step in the state's control of Camden came the
day after Milan was charged in an indictment with extortion, money
laundering and mail fraud. Federal authorities said Milan accepted
payoffs and gifts from city contractors and took bribes from
organized crime figures.
</P>
<P>
   The state gave Milan two weeks to correct long-standing
problems. The state finance board said he didn't and on April 14
voted to place the city under supervision. That prompted the state
Attorney General's Office to file a lawsuit that asked a judge to
approve the control measures.
</P>
<P>
   Milan threatened to place the city in bankruptcy last year
before he accepted a deal to allow a state financial review board
some oversight of operations. But despite that monitoring, the
state alleges, Camden officials continued to ignore the problems.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, the state said Camden filed annual audits more
than two years after they were due. When the audits were filed,
some contained a notice from the auditor that the examinations
could not be done because Camden kept no records of its
expenditures. Camden also overspent its budget by nearly $500,000
in 1998, according to the state's legal brief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-25-00 1830 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000525.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group says state could save $96 million on prisons  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER JORDAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The state spends $96 million a year on
''unnecessary and sometimes counterproductive'' imprisonment, a
fiscal watchdog group reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   By expanding shock camps, drug treatment, electronically
monitored house arrests and an agency to evaluate prison policies,
the Department of Correctional Services could trim 4 percent from
its $2.3 billion on prisons, the Citizens Budget Commission said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying to say you can run the prison system smarter by
offering alternatives,'' said spokesman Charles Brecher.
</P>
<P>
   The group estimated that savings could come from the following
areas:
</P>
<P>
   --$65 million if nonviolent drug offenders were eligible for
prison alternatives like drug treatment or shock camp after one
year. Many are in prisons at least two years, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   --$20 million if electronically monitored house arrests were
substituted for prison for the last six months of sentencing for
nonviolent property crimes like trespassing, burglary without
intent to harm and cemetery desecration.
</P>
<P>
   --$11 million by releasing violent offenders who are paroled two
months earlier and employing electronically monitored house arrest
and stricter parole supervision. Citizens Budget Commission also
said this could improve public safety.
</P>
<P>
   The group also said inmates 50 years or older may be good
candidates for alternate sanctions like home confinement or
intensive parole since studies suggest criminal activity declines
with age.
</P>
<P>
   The Citizens Budget Commission admitted its cost calculations
are ''necessarily highly speculative.''
</P>
<P>
   Correctional Services spokesman James Flateau noted that 26,000
inmates are already in shock or alternate treatment programs or
have had their sentences shortened for participating in them. He
said corrections officials believe trustworthy nonviolent inmates
in the system are already taking advantage of programs to shorten
sentences and that the Citizens Budget Commission is advocating
that prisoners who would pose a risk to the public inappropriately
now be included.
</P>
<P>
   ''Who are the inmates they are talking about?'' he asked.
''Violent inmates ... people who already flunked out (of
treatment)?''
</P>
<P>
   He denied that there is $20 million available in savings
involving the nonviolent property crimes described by the group
because virtually all of those offenders are sent to local jails,
not state prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Flateau also said that the department itself does not have the
authority to make some of the changes the group called for but
would need to be directed to do so by Gov. George Pataki and the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ''There certainly is some expansion (Corrections) can do without
authority,'' Brecher said. ''But it certainly would be better to
have everybody on board.''
</P>
<P>
   The Citizens Budget Commission also recommended expanding what
it said was a 19-person agency in Corrections to come up with new
alternatives to imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Flateau, however, said the Division of Program Planning,
Research and Development is sufficient, though he could not confirm
how many people work there.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time the 68-year-old Citizens Budget
Commission, which has criticized the state budget process in the
past, has analyzed criminal justice.
</P>
<P>
   The report adds a new argument -- cost -- to the growing
complaints about the Rockefeller Drug Laws. Often those laws have
been called too harsh on moral or philosophical grounds by groups
as diverse as the state's Roman Catholic bishops to the top judges
in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The Citizens Budget Commission blamed a rise in imprisonment on
policies like Jenna's Law, which effectively eliminated parole for
a person who committed one violent crime, and the Rockefeller Drug
Laws. An official with the group suggested those laws are based on
emotional or political reasoning instead of deterrence.
</P>
<P>
   Janice Grieshaber, whose daughter's murder by a parolee spurred
Jenna's Law, was not impressed with the Citizens Budget
Commission's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you want to weigh dollars and people, in my opinion people
win,'' she said. ''Nicholas Pryor saw his parole officer at 3 and
murdered my daughter at 6 p.m. so I don't know how you can use cost
in this particular case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
