<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quinnipiac poll gives Corzine substantial lead in Senate race  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A Quinnipiac College poll released Thursday
gives U.S. Senate candidate Jon Corzine an overwhelming lead over
former Gov. Jim Florio in the Democratic primary race.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-six percent of the registered Democrats who said they were
likely to vote June 6 said they would vote for Corzine, with 30
percent saying they would support Florio. Fourteen percent said
they were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns questioned the result and said their information
shows the race to be tighter.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not taking this poll seriously,'' said Florio adviser
Walter Fields.
</P>
<P>
   The money race was even more lopsided as federal campaign
finance reports filed Thursday showed Corzine had spent $23.5
million in the primary contest as of May 17 compared with Florio's
spending of $1.4 million. Corzine himself said he expected to spend
$2 million a week on TV commercials in the final 20 days between
the May 17 report to the June 6 primary.
</P>
<P>
   Quinnipiac College of Hamden, Conn., questioned 371 likely
Democratic voters from May 17-23. The poll has a margin of error of
5.1 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Quinnipiac College political analyst Scott McLean said Florio
may still gain some support as his TV ads begin, but he said there
do not appear to be many minds left to be made up.
</P>
<P>
   While questioning the margin, Corzine spokesman Steve Goldstein
said the poll result is consistent with his camp's sense of the
campaign's direction. In a poll released in March, Corzine trailed
Florio by a 2-to-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both Corzine and Florio (internal) polls show this race to be
substantially closer, and either side can win, but the trend is
unmistakable toward Jon Corzine, and it proves that the voters of
New Jersey find Jim Florio to be as repellent as a can of bug spray
on the hot summer night,'' Goldstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Fields said the Florio campaign also anticipates a much tighter
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have never put any credence in a Quinnipiac Poll, even when
they had us up by a ridiculous margin. We have always believed this
is going to be a close race,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quinnipiac released a poll May 10 giving Corzine a 48-33 lead
over Florio, but both campaigns and many political analysts
discounted the numbers because the polling institute had not
screened respondents to see if they intended to vote. The survey
dealt only with registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   The poll released Thursday copied that question, asking 944
registered Democrats their opinion, and they gave Corzine a 47-28
lead, close to the May 10 result.
</P>
<P>
   But the new poll also took the next step, breaking out responses
from the 371 Democrats who said they intended to vote June 6, which
yielded the more lopsided 56-30 margin.
</P>
<P>
   After releasing its May 10 poll, Quinnipiac had said it did not
intend to release any before June 6.
</P>
<P>
   ''We changed our minds because we ended up getting enough likely
voters to do something with it,'' McLean said. ''Our previous poll
was criticized for not including likely Democratic primary voters,
and we came right back with a poll that did include those voters,
and the trends still hold from two weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fields said Quinnipiac's credibility was compromised by the
last poll. ''We don't believe the poll should be trusted, and we
think the only reason they commissioned another poll is they are
trying to save face,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, a retired Wall Street executive who has spent lavishly
on television advertising, and Florio are running for the seat
being vacated by Democrat Frank Lautenberg, who is retiring at the
end of his term.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.quinnipiac.edu
</P>
<P>
   http://www.votecorzine.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.florionj.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
