<DOCNO> APW20000525.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suerfund Might Exempt Small Cos.  </HEADLINE>
By LIB QUAID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Under legislation introduced Thursday, small
companies could skirt the Environmental Protection Agency's
Superfund program, which currently requires them to pay to clean up
toxic sites they created or added to.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher Bond, R-Mo., wants to exempt companies with
fewer than 100 workers from liability unless they are guilty of
gross negligence or significantly contributed to a site.
</P>
<P>
   The Superfund program never was intended to punish restaurant
owners or other mom-and-pop businesses that legally hauled garbage
to Superfund sites, Bond said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Innocent Main Street small business owners across the nation
continue to be unfairly pulled into Superfund's legal quagmire,''
said Bond, who chairs the Small Business Committee.
</P>
<P>
   EPA Administrator Carol Browner and other agency officials have
repeatedly expressed support for reforms along those lines.
</P>
<P>
   But it already has upset the environmental lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't want to leave the taxpayers footing the bill for
cleanup of toxic waste sites, whether they're left by little guys
or big guys,'' the Sierra Club's Kathryn Hohman said. ''Small
parties can make big messes.''
</P>
<P>
   Exempting small businesses from the Superfund's tough
regulations would remove a powerful incentive to behave
responsibly, said Deb Callahan, executive director of the League of
Conservation Voters. ''This undermines some of the fundamental
concepts of the Superfund program,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan said Bond, a frequent target of her group, ''isn't the
kind of senator we would trust to rewrite toxic waste law in the
public interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond aide Tracy Henke said the measure doesn't let polluters off
the hook.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those who have violated the law are still required to pay,''
Henke said. ''It's just that while Senator Bond believes small
business owners are innocent, groups like the Sierra Club would
rather insist they're guilty until proven innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is S-2634.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-25-00 1900 </TRAILER>
