<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Supreme Court affirms 100 percent funding for poor schools  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The New Jersey Supreme Court Thursday
affirmed its earlier order that the state must pay full funding for
construction projects in 30 poor school districts.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is a defeat for Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, who
last month asked the justices to clarify a 1998 ruling that most
interpreted as ordering 100 percent state funding for the so-called
''special-needs'' schools.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, R-Salem, whose original school construction legislation
fell short of that mandate, argued that the 1998 decision was not
clear. He also argued that the court should have granted the
Legislature some leeway in portioning funds to the districts, which
are not uniformly poor.
</P>
<P>
   But the justices, in an unanimous nine-page decision, said their
1998 order stands.
</P>
<P>
   ''The state is required to fund all of the costs of necessary
facilities, remediation and construction in the Abbott districts,''
the decision said, referring to the special-needs districts' name
in the Abbott vs. Burke court case.
</P>
<P>
   David Sciarra of the Education Law Center, which sued the state
on behalf of the poor schools, said Thursday he was not surprised
at the justices' ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''We always thought that the court's (1998) decision was clear,
now it's crystal clear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said Thursday he will abide by the court ruling, and
change his school construction bill to reflect full funding. His
original legislation provided the poor schools 100 percent funding
only for emergency repairs and projects designed to ease classroom
overcrowding, but fewer dollars for extra items such as cafeterias
and media centers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Is 100 percent really 100 percent? Now we have the answer,''
Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   On the constitutional issue, the speaker said the Legislature
deserved more input in determining state funding levels for the
poor schools. It was the executive branch, not lawmakers, who
recommended full funding when the school funding case was before
the Supreme Court in 1997 and 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm troubled by that,'' he said. ''We're the appropriating
body. But the court has spoken so our bill will comply with 100
percent funding.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins' decision to change his bill brings him in accord with
Gov. Christie Whitman and Senate President Donald DiFrancesco, who
have backed a competing bill supplying 100 percent funding for poor
schools.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco, who like Collins is a possible gubernatorial
candidate in 2001, issued a statement applauding the court for
clarifying its intent. He said Thursday's ruling clears the way for
final passage of the school construction bill, which has languished
during months of gridlock between the legislative leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But DiFrancesco also sounded a cautionary note.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hopefully, pending revisions will not throw further roadblocks
in the way of enacting this important property tax relief
initiative this spring,'' his statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has already passed a $15 billion school construction
bill. Collins' version is pending in the lower house. The speaker
said it is scheduled for consideration by the Assembly
Appropriations Committee on June 1.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman Thursday said she was pleased the court affirmed its
early ruling, but warned that the pending legislation is growing
too expensive. The bill also provides partial funding for more
affluent suburban schools. Annual payments totaling $15 billion are
expected to rise over its 30-year term.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the out years, this won't be a problem with my budget as a
governor, but a problem with my budget as a homeowner in the state
of New Jersey,'' said Whitman, who has less than two years
remaining in office.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, back from a trade mission to the Far East, raised
red flags about Senate plans to provide retroactive aid to some
school districts that started construction projects before the 1998
court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''I started out with what I thought was the most fiscally
manageable proposal,'' she said. ''My concern is going way back.
When do you say stop?''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he also was worried about the pricetag, and said he
may amend his version of the bill to include a cap on annual
spending. He would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The state education commissioner will have the final say over
what kinds of projects fit the court's criteria as educationally
''necessary'' to prevent state funding of such projects as
''Olympic size athletic complexes,'' Whitman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
