<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Helps Maintain Weight Loss  </HEADLINE>
By EMMA ROSS
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANTWERP, Belgium (AP) -- Obese people who continued using the
drug sibutramine 18 months after they lost weight were able to keep
it off, but those who stopped taking the pills regained the pounds,
new research shows.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the experiment with the drug, which is used as a
weight-loss aid by 2 million people worldwide -- 1.6 million of them
in the United States -- were presented this week at the European
Congress on Obesity.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very important finding because it changes the
philosophy of how to use the drug,'' said Michel Carruba, professor
of pharmacology at the University of Milan, who was not involved
with the study. ''Doctors use the drug to obtain weight loss, but
the main job the drug does is ... (to help) control behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Dieters have had little in the way of drugs to rely on since the
recall in 1997 of half the popular anti-obesity cocktail
fenfleuramine-phentermine, or fen-phen, after it was linked with
potentially fatal heart-valve damage.
</P>
<P>
   Sibutramine, known as Meridia in the United States and as
Reductil elsewhere, acts on the brain chemicals which regulate food
intake and energy burning.
</P>
<P>
   Sibutramine's side effects include increased heart rate and
blood pressure, along with insomnia, but Carruba said those effects
do not cause significant trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Carruba said it was safer that fen-phen because ''you can use it
long-term.'' He also praised the study as being well-conducted and
''one of the best studies that's ever been done on obesity drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   In the two-year study, 400 Europeans were given a typical 10 mg
dose of sibutramine daily for six months, were told to exercise
regularly and were offered intensive diet counseling
</P>
<P>
   After the six months, 100 were given a fake pill and the rest
continued to take the drug, at doses tailored to each person.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen months later, weight loss was sustained in those taking
sibutramine, but for those who had stopped, the weight gradually
came back.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a progressive difference between the two groups as
the study went on,'' said Dr. Arne Astrup, a professor of nutrition
at the University of Copenhagen who was involved in the study.''
</P>
<P>
   Cholesterol dropped in the drug group by the same amount that it
normally does with standard cholesterol-lowering drugs, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ''This individual obesity-management program can achieve and
maintain metabolically significant weight loss in 77 percent of
obese patients who continue for two years,'' the study said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-25-00 1913 </TRAILER>
