<HEADLINE> Documents Linked to No Gun Ri  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   A look at documents obtained by The Associated Press:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Records recently obtained by The Associated Press place Edward
L. Daily in the 27th Ordnance Maintenance Company consistently
between March 1949 and March 1951.
</P>
<P>
   Daily originally maintained that he was in H Company, 2nd
Battalion, 7th Cavalry Regiment during that period, and
participated in the killing of South Korean civilians on July
26-29, 1950, by U.S. soldiers at a railroad trestle near a hamlet
called No Gun Ri.
</P>
<P>
   Daily's name appears in the semiannual 27th Ordnance Maintenance
Company roster for the following dates:
</P>
<P>
   July 31, 1949
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 31, 1950
</P>
<P>
   July 31, 1950
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 31, 1951
</P>
<P>
   Daily's name appears in 27th Ordnance Maintenance Company
documents -- including morning reports, daily accountings of the
comings-and-goings of unit members -- on the following dates:
</P>
<P>
   March 9, 1949: Transferred to the 27th Ordnance Maintenance
Company from the 2nd Replacement Battalion. A special order
attached to the morning report on this day lists Daily as one of 33
men assigned to the 27th Ordnance.
</P>
<P>
   April 7, 1949: Special order cited in the morning report shows
Daily was attached, for rations and quarters only, to the 92nd
Anti-Aircraft Artillery Company in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 19, 1949: Memorandum to the commanding officer of the 27th
Ordnance Maintenance shows Daily among soldiers whose enlistment
was extended.
</P>
<P>
   July 10, 1950: Morning report shows that Daily's temporary
attachment to 92nd AAA was terminated as the 27th Ordnance
Maintenance prepared to deploy to Korea.
</P>
<P>
   July 26, 1950: Morning report shows that the 27th Ordnance
Maintenance arrived by ship at Pohang-dong, Korea, 80 miles east of
No Gun Ri.
</P>
<P>
   July 27, 1950: Morning report shows the 27th arrived at Kumchon,
18 miles east of No Gun Ri.
</P>
<P>
   July 28, 1950: Morning report shows the 27th Ordnance
Maintenance left Kumchon and pulled back to Waegwan. (It remained
there until Aug. 3.)
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 22, 1950: Morning report shows Daily's job classification
changed from clerk to mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 31, 1951: Morning report shows Daily sent to a
quartermaster depot in Tokyo for five days.
</P>
<P>
   March 13, 1951: Morning report shows he returned from temporary
duty in Tokyo effective Feb. 2, 1951.
</P>
<P>
   March 22, 1951: Morning report shows Daily is reassigned from
27th Ordnance Maintenance to H Company, 7th Cavalry Regiment.
</P>
<P>
   March 24, 1951: H Company morning report notes Daily was
reassigned to the company and his job classification was changed to
heavy weapons infantryman.
</P>
<P>
   May 10, 1951: H Company morning report shows Daily reassigned to
a replacement unit for rotation out of Korea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
