<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Delays Doctor Bill Vote  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rising opposition in the Republican ranks has
sidetracked a promise by House Speaker Dennis Hastert to take up a
bill that would give self-employed doctors new rights to bargain
collectively with HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   The House Rules Committee, which sets procedure and acts as a
gateway for bills moving to the floor, decided Wednesday to put off
action on the bill, at least until after the House returns from its
weeklong Memorial Day holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was late at night and the votes weren't there to move it,''
Hastert, R-Ill., said Thursday. ''And we didn't want to lose it.''
He said he still intends to bring it up at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   The American Medical Association expressed outrage over the
committee's inaction.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is hard to imagine a more outrageous subversion of the
American democratic process,'' said Dr. D. Ted Lewers, chairman of
the AMA board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert has promised Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., the chief
sponsor and a challenger for Democratic Sen. Dianne Feinstein's
Senate seat, that he would get a vote on his legislation. Campbell
reportedly has said the House must move now to allow time for
Senate action this year.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, at their closed-door weekly meeting, a
majority of House Republicans voted for a resolution, proposed by
Rep. Anne Northup of Kentucky, to delay a vote on the doctor bill
until Congress dispenses with a larger HMO patient bill of rights
that has been stalled in a House-Senate conference.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't get the two-thirds vote they needed to approve the
resolution, but found a sympathetic ear with Republicans on the
Rules Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''The members of the committee were all in agreement that the
bill was not ready,'' said Richard Mills, spokesman for the
committee chairman, Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif. ''There wasn't a
comfort level in the conference to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They're trying to throw the bill overboard, it seems,'' said
Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., the leading Democratic sponsor of the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which is backed by the American Medical Association,
would amend antitrust laws to give health care professionals the
right to bargain collectively with health plans over fees and other
contract terms.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell says the bill is pro-consumer because it would allow
health care professionals to join together to fight gag rules,
limits on testing and other restrictions imposed by health
maintenance organizations. But the new bargaining power, already
enjoyed by doctors employed by a hospital or municipality, does not
give doctors the right to strike.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is facing fierce opposition from a coalition of health
insurance, HMO, hospital and business groups that say it could
drive up health costs and private health insurance premiums and
disrupt patient care.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to delay a vote, said Karen Ignagni, president of
the American Association of Health Plans, ''is definitely a sign
that members of Congress want to slow down and look at the
implications of this.''
</P>
<P>
   She said her organization of HMOs and preferred provider
organizations, which is leading the drive against the bill, regards
it as ''the most significant piece of anti-consumer legislation in
decades.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 1304.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The AAHP site: http://www.aahp.org.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell site: http://www.house.gov/campbell/000516.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-25-00 1916 </TRAILER>
