<HEADLINE> Barak Delivers Messages to Lebanon  </HEADLINE>
By SARI BASHI
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRYAT SHEMONA, Israel (AP) -- Speaking to a special session of
parliament on Israel's northern border, Prime Minister Ehud Barak
delivered a double message to Lebanon on Thursday: Israel stretches
out its hand in peace, but will deliver a punishing blow if
attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking a day after the last Israeli soldier left Lebanon,
ending 18 years of occupation, Barak also told Lebanon that Israel
no longer occupies any of its territory, a reference to the
dismantling of border outposts that had jutted out into Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The special parliamentary session in Kiryat Shemona -- a town hit
by 4,000 rockets fired from Lebanon over the last two decades -- was
a message of solidarity with residents who fear Israel's pullout
endangers their security.
</P>
<P>
   The border has been quiet since the withdrawal, but Barak warned
he would hit back if guerrillas on the border attacked Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Israel would see this as an act of war, and no target or
source of power in Lebanon would be immune from a harsh response,''
he said, in a veiled reference to Syria, which has 30,000 troops in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   He followed the threat, however, with a call for neighborly
relations, acknowledging Syria's influence in Lebanon, but seeking
to bypass it with a direct appeal to Lebanon's president.
</P>
<P>
   ''I call on you, President Emile Lahoud, Israel extends its hand
in peace,'' Barak said. ''Israel is not Lebanon's enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak praised Lebanon's economic recovery and expressed hope
that it would continue.
</P>
<P>
   Barak spokesman David Ziso said work dismantling border outposts
technically located in Lebanon had been completed. But Israel is
still building its new fence along the international border and the
old one which juts out into Lebanon in some places has not been
taken down.
</P>
<P>
   Bulldozers cleared land for the new fence Thursday, and soldiers
set up checkpoints blocking civilian access to the border.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's withdrawal of all its soldiers and outposts allows the
United Nations to verify the withdrawal, a precondition for sending
peacekeeping troops.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, speaking Thursday to
reporters in Washington, said after formal confirmation of the
pullout he hopes to announce ''within days'' plans to boost the
interim force of 4,500 troops, who have been in Lebanon since 1978,
to about 8,000. The new troops, to be used to ensure peace along
the Israeli-Lebanon border, should be in the region ''within
weeks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Conscious of the security fears of northern residents, Barak
left the parliament session for a campaign-style tour, popping into
a local falafel stand for a snack and shaking hands with
demonstrators applauding the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in a counter-demonstration accused him of
abandoning front-line communities.
</P>
<P>
   ''We respect that the Knesset (parliament) has come here,''
Kiryat Shemona Mayor Haim Barbivai said. ''But we know they can't
give us the security we want.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiryat Shemona residents spent the beginning of this week in
shelters, fearful of rocket attacks in retaliation for civilian
deaths in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Barak praised frontier residents as heroes and called upon
Israelis to visit northern resorts, which have been badly hit
economically by the fighting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-25-00 1917 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000525.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Receives Security Advice  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An internal report on improving State
Department security recommends limiting traffic in surrounding
streets to people with proper clearance, screening all cars using
the basement parking garage and bolstering the building's
400-member security detail, a senior official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Also, security checks of all employees and visitors should take
place outside the two-square block building instead of inside -- one
of the 43 recommendations made by the department's top security
adviser, said the official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright received the report May 19
from Assistant Secretary of State David Carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   One of the streets that runs next to the department is expected
to be closed because of street construction. Security concerns may
keep the street closed after that work is done.
</P>
<P>
   Security has become a high priority for Albright following
several embarrassing violations in recent months. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   --In February, a laptop computer containing highly classified
information disappeared from the department's Bureau of
Intelligence and Research.
</P>
<P>
   --Last fall, the department uncovered a Russian spy operation
involving a bug planted in a seventh floor conference room. A
Russian agent involved in the operation was expelled from the
country in December.
</P>
<P>
   --Earlier this month, two General Accounting Office guards posing
as New York City police officers wandered the building unescorted
for 15 minutes, officials disclosed Thursday. Under department
rules, the two should have been under escort at all times.
</P>
<P>
   The two were testing State Department security arrangements as
part of a congressionally mandated investigation to review security
at 19 government installations and two commercial airports. In each
case, the GAO agents used fake credentials to get past security
guards.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact that they were not escorted out of here was a
mistake,'' Carpenter said. Another official said the agents, on
entering the building, said they were armed but conceded days later
that they were unarmed.
</P>
<P>
   The episode produced an immediate policy change -- no one can
enter the State Department armed except for federal law enforcers
on official business, according to the official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
