<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angels' Shortstop Out for Season  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Shortstop Gary DiSarcina, an Anaheim
Angels' leader both on the field and in the clubhouse, is expected
to miss the rest of the season after undergoing surgery on his
right shoulder Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina is in the final year of a four-year, $11.7 million
contract that includes a $3.45 million option for 2001 -- which
becomes guaranteed if he makes 1,200 plate appearances in the last
three seasons of the contract. He now has only 900 at-bats in that
span.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the Angels could decline the option, which would make
him eligible for free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Team medical director Dr. Lewis Yocum repaired a small tear to
DiSarcina's rotator cuff and trimmed the outer layer of the labrum,
part of the shoulder joint, during the operation at University of
California-Irvine Medical Center in Orange.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina, 32, was batting .395 with one home runs and 11 RBIs
in 12 games this season.
</P>
<P>
   He initially was placed on the 15-day disabled list on April 9
with a bruised left thumb. He was activated April 24, but went back
on the DL because of stiffness in his right shoulder on May 8.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina has played in 1,086 games for the Angels, most among
their active players and is tied for fourth all-time with Dick
Schofield.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina has a career mark of .258, with 28 homers and 355
RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Benji Gil, who has made nine errors and is hitting .225, has
filled in at short for the Angels. Justin Baughman, a former second
baseman now playing shortstop at Triple-A Edmonton, could
eventually move into the position for Anaheim.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
