<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Laws Sought on Web Pharmacies  </HEADLINE>
By G. STEPHEN BIERMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- New laws are needed for regulating online
pharmacies that are writing prescriptions and selling drugs over
the Internet, often illegally, the Clinton administration told
Congress on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A House subcommittee taking it first look at the
administration's proposal submitted earlier this month was told how
the spiraling growth in sales of prescription drugs over the
Internet is overwhelming drug safety regulators and law enforcement
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, a 16-year-old boy bought Viagra and two other
controlled substances from a doctor's Web site after only filling
out a diagnostic questionnaire. The physician was prosecuted under
a state law, but only because he sold the drugs to a minor.
</P>
<P>
   ''Online pharmacy sites often circumvent the traditional
protections built into the doctor-patient relationship, such as
diagnosis based on a physical examination,'' Deputy Associate
Attorney General Ethan Posner told the House Commerce
investigations subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Posner said, the government has largely relied on
health professionals -- physicians and pharmacists -- to protect
patients from knowingly or accidentally misusing prescribed
medicines that could cause them harm.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to need some legislation that will better define
the law and provide more tools to enforce it, particularly where
folk are getting access to prescriptions without a doctor's
prescription itself,'' said Fred Upton, R-Mich., the subcommittee's
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas Attorney General Carla J. Stovall said differing state
laws and evasive practices have made regulating Internet pharmacies
and prosecuting illegal prescription sales both difficult and
time-consuming.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all had to sort through multiple shell corporations,
addresses that turned out to be mail drops, and overlapping
physical and Internet addresses shared by different entities,'' she
said. ''Companies selling dangerous drugs across state lines should
be required to maintain current, accurate, accessible information
about their principals, their physical addresses and their
identities.''
</P>
<P>
   All of that would be required under legislation that the Food
and Drug Administration submitted to Congress earlier this month.
The FDA-sought law also would require online pharmacies to be
licensed in each state in which they operate or deliver
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Posner said the Justice Department has opened about 30
investigations in the past year in online pharmaceutical sales and
has indicted at least one person for selling Viagra over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Internet access to European, Asian and Central American
pharmacies that sell drugs without prescriptions also has put
pressure on the U.S. Customs Service.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Durant, director of trade programs for the Customs
Service, said the number of pharmaceuticals seized entering the
United States jumped 450 percent from 1998 to 1999, an increase of
7,586 seizures.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: National Association of Boards of Pharmacy:
http://www.nabp.org
</P>
<P>
   Department of Justice: http://www.usdoj.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-25-00 1944 </TRAILER>
