<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers Head to Portland  </HEADLINE>
By BOB BAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The last time the Los Angeles Lakers came
to Portland, it was billed as the biggest game of the NBA season.
This one's bigger.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers finally headed to the Northwest on Thursday for the
resumption of the Western Conference finals Friday night with Game
3 in what is bound to be a rockin' and rollin' Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   After splitting two games in Los Angeles, the Trail Blazers,
backed by their loud, loyal fans, have the homecourt advantage, for
the rest of this series and in the finals, too, if they make it
that far.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we defend our homecourt from here in, we're crowned the
champion,'' Portland's Scottie Pippen said. ''That's how we look at
it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an observation that has to irritate coach Phil Jackson and
his Lakers, who won 67 regular-season games to earn the homecourt
edge throughout the playoffs, only to see it slip away in an
embarrassing 106-77 loss in Game 2 Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   When the two teams last met in Portland, on Feb. 29, both were
45-11 and both were on 11-game winning streaks. Los Angeles won
90-87, and the Blazers, who later lost Arvydas Sabonis and Brian
Grant to injuries, never could pull even again.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers need another Rose Garden triumph, either Friday or in
Game 4 Sunday, or they will return to Los Angeles for Game 5 in big
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important that we come here and really push them farther
into a corner,'' Pippen said. ''Right now we've got a great
opportunity to really put their backs against the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, just 1-3 on the road in the playoffs, have mentioned
that February victory often as they try to regroup from their worst
loss of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Lakers left Los Angeles on Thursday, Jackson talked
about that makes a good road team.
</P>
<P>
   ''That they're able to sustain adversity on the road, stay with
their game plan, play solid defense, don't turn the ball over a
lot,'' Jackson said. ''Winning on the road is one of the great
pleasures of NBA basketball, especially in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal scored 41 points in Game 1, a memorable
afternoon in which Portland coach Mike Dunleavy took the
Hack-a-Shaq tactics to record highs, or lows, depending on your
opinion of the strategy.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neal scored only 23 in Game 2, 14 of them in what
essentially was a meaningless final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   He was persistently double-teamed, often unable to find a clear
passing route through the long arms of Pippen or Rasheed Wallace.
But his path will be easier, Jackson said, if the Lakers can hit
from the outside, as they did in Game 1, and Kobe Bryant, averaging
just nine shots and 12.5 points in the series, can get his offense
going.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't think Shaq had that bad a game Monday night,''
Jackson said. ''He got in foul trouble, just didn't have that much
roaming space, took a few bad shots. I think Shaq's always
aggressive. I think Kobe's got to shoot the basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, who played on six NBA championship teams, has emerged as
the Blazers' unquestioned leader, something the Portland teams of
the recent past have sorely lacked.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd say the thing that puts him in the lead are those six
things,'' Wallace said. ''I would say he's the premier leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, and his teammates, seemed amused but not unruffled by
Jackson's between-game remarks. Jackson said the Blazers behaved
like jackals on the bench in their celebration after Game 2, and he
accused Pippen of playing zone defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''My response is that he should concentrate on being a coach and
stop trying to referee,'' Pippen said.
</P>
<P>
   With Friday night's game, Pippen will move ahead of Danny Ainge
into the No. 2 spot for NBA playoff appearances with 194.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since the playoffs began, he's done a 360 in his role as a
leader,'' Grant said. ''During the season, he was trying to make
other guys better. Not that he's not doing that now, but it seems
as soon as the playoffs started, he took on a whole new role
offensively.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whereas he was more swinging it to get other guys open, now
he'll look to swing it and if nobody's there, he's going to go. We
know he's going to go, and that's what we need him to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
