<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corzine spending at $27 million, closing in on California record  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- U.S. Senate candidate Jon Corzine has spent
more than $27 million so far in his quest to beat former Gov. Jim
Florio in the race for the Democratic primary nomination, and he
could spend another $5 million through Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's report to the Federal Elections Commission filed
Thursday showed he had spent $25 million as of May 17 and had
obligated his campaign to another $2.2 million in debts, contracts
and bills yet to be paid.
</P>
<P>
   Florio's FEC report showed he had spent $1.9 million by the same
date. Both figures include spending for 1999, $3.7 million by
Corzine, $466,000 by Florio.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said Monday he spend at least another $2 million per
week on TV commercials for the final two weeks of the campaign,
although a portion of that could have been contracted by May 17. He
is also expected to deploy large sums on Primary Day in
get-out-the-vote efforts like phone banks and van shuttles.
</P>
<P>
   The historic pace of spending is unprecedented in any race for a
seat in the U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The May 17 report brings the self-financing Wall Street
millionaire to within a few big checks of shattering the national
record set in 1994 by another self-financing candidate, Republican
Senate candidate Michael Huffington in California, a state with
four times New Jersey's population. Huffington spent $30 million
that year, less than a third of that in his primary contest. He
ended up losing to U.S. Sen. Dianne Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   The lopsided money tally in the New Jersey Democratic primary
comes along with a Quinnipiac College poll released Thursday giving
Corzine an overwhelming lead over Florio. Fifty-six percent of the
registered Democrats who said they were likely to vote backed
Corzine compared to 30 percent for Florio; 14 percent were
undecided. The poll had a margin of error of 5.1 percentage points,
which even when skewed to Florio's advantage gives Corzine a 16
point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns denounced the poll, saying their research shows
the race to be closer, although Corzine spokesman Steve Goldstein
said the Quinnipiac result did comport with their findings that
Corzine has been rising steadily in voter support.
</P>
<P>
   While Corzine has largely been funding his campaign himself, the
reports to the FEC show he has raised $2.5 million in individual
contributions, $1.1 million of it since Jan. 1. The reports show
Florio has raised $1.6 million, $557,000 of it from Jan. 1 to May.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis by the Center for Responsive Politics, a watchdog
group, showed that in March, Florio was getting 79 percent of his
donations from within New Jersey while Corzine was getting 63
percent of his donations from outside the state.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.votecorzine.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.florionj.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-25-00 2010 </TRAILER>
