<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Debate About Debate  </HEADLINE>
By MARK STEVENSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A conservative opposition party has reined in
its brash presidential candidate, Vicente Fox, getting him to agree
to the debate that critics say he wanted to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who has the best chance in seven decades to unseat the
ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party candidate, has had his
image tarnished by the controversy over the three-way debate.
</P>
<P>
   Because Fox, a plainspoken farm owner and businessman, feared
the ruling party's nominee and a left-center rival would gang up on
him in Friday's televised debate, he stalled on agreeing to
conditions for the debate. Then, on television Tuesday, he suddenly
reversed course and demanded a debate that same day, over the
objections of his rivals.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the ruling party's Francisco Labastida and
left-center candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas stuck to the Friday
format.
</P>
<P>
   Diego Fernandez, a top leader of Fox's National Action Party,
called the television spectacle a ''pre-planned ambush.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying Fox's strategy ''needed to be adjusted,'' National Action
Party president Luis Felipe Bravo met with Fox Wednesday and
persuaded him to participate in Friday's debate, local media
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Though expressing his usual confidence, Fox said he was going
into the debate with some trepidation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will confront the alliance of Cardenas with Labastida which
is trying to preserve the authoritarian system of corruption and
privileges imposed on Mexican society for the past 70 years,'' Fox
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's reluctance to agree to debate terms was widely seen as a
bid to preserve the momentum he gained in the first TV encounter
between the candidates in April. After that debate, Fox pulled
roughly even with Labastida in polls.
</P>
<P>
   But the disagreement goes to the heart of the July 2 elections.
It illustrates how little hope remains of an alliance between
Cardenas and Fox -- a step many see as the only hope of beating the
ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, which has held Mexico's
presidency since 1929.
</P>
<P>
   Months ago, the two parties had tried to form a wide,
anti-ruling party coalition, but it collapsed because of procedural
and ideological wrangling and that fact that Fox and Cardenas
dislike each other.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Cardenas has focused his fire almost
exclusively on Fox, rather than the left's traditional target, the
ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be foolishness, it would be stubbornness that would
be governing if he (Fox) is not headed off in time,'' Cardenas said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over the debate also points up some weaknesses in
Fox's otherwise winning personality.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fox did everything humanly possible to sink the debate,''
columnist Julio Hernandez wrote in the newspaper La Jornada. ''Fox
parked himself on Stubborn Street, and then put on the emergency
brake.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-25-00 2011 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000525.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAA Orders New Plane Insulation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Aviation Administration ordered
the operators of 719 Boeing aircraft Thursday to replace insulation
blankets covered with a form of Mylar that could increase the risk
of a fire spreading.
</P>
<P>
   The agency directive applies to MD-80, MD-88, MD-90, DC-10 and
MD-11 aircraft designed by McDonnell Douglas, which Boeing bought
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ''The risk of fire aboard these aircraft is very low, but this
is a prudent action to take to raise the bar on safety,'' FAA
Administrator Jane F. Garvey said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing spokesman John Thom said the company will work with
aircraft operators to help them comply with the FAA order.
</P>
<P>
   The order affects 719 U.S.-registered aircraft operated by
Alaska Airlines, American Airlines, Boeing, Continental Airlines,
Delta Air Lines, Federal Express, Frontier Airlines, Midwest
Express, Northwest Airlines, Spirit Airlines, Trans World Airlines,
US Airways and World Airways.
</P>
<P>
   The operators have five years to replace the insulation
blankets, a process that will cost about $368 million.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,500 of the planes operate worldwide, but the FAA can
only require changes by U.S. carriers. Other countries normally
follow the U.S. lead in such orders.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, the FAA ordered U.S. airlines to conduct emergency
inspections of 120 Boeing 767 aircraft after mechanics found
damaged bolts in one plane's engine pylons.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Boeing:http://www.boeing.com
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration:
http://www.faa.gov/apa/pr/index.cfm
</P>
</TEXT>
