<HEADLINE> Gay Republicans Criticize Party  </HEADLINE>
By KELLY SHANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN (AP) -- The Log Cabin Republicans of Texas criticized the
state Republican party Thursday for not reaching out to gay and
lesbian voters. They pledged to set up an exhibit booth outside the
party's upcoming state convention.
</P>
<P>
   The group said Texas Gov. George W. Bush is not involved in the
convention planning because he is involved in his presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush recently met with national gay leaders and the Log Cabin
Republicans national organization, which represents gay and lesbian
Republicans, is considering whether to endorse Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Scott McClellan, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, said the
specific issue of the booths should be settled by the state party.
But, he said: ''Governor Bush believes in treating all individuals
with dignity and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas group urged the state party to respond to its
requests.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our group's message is simple -- one can be a Republican and
oppose discrimination,'' said Steve Labinski, president of the Log
Cabin Republicans of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The group contends the Republican Party of Texas has refused to
respond to its request to operate an information booth at the state
political convention June 15-17 at the George R. Brown Convention
Center in Houston. State party officials deny the group requested a
convention booth.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of setting up inside the convention center, the group
will establish an information booth outside, Labinski said, adding
that more than 50 members of the gay Republican group are among the
8,700 delegates to the party's state convention.
</P>
<P>
   The Log Cabin Republicans asked for booth space at the 1996
state convention in San Antonio but were turned down. The
organization sued the state party, but the Texas Supreme Court
ultimately sided with the GOP.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
