<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Troops Urged To Give Up  </HEADLINE>
By LAURINDA KEYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Separatist rebels in Sri Lanka warned
the thousands of government troops defending the island's northern
city of Jaffna -- surrender by Friday or face a ''blood bath.''
</P>
<P>
   As the rebels pressed their offensive against Jaffna, their
clandestine radio station broadcast the ultimatum, saying soldiers
who laid down their arms by Friday at 6 p.m. would be handed over
to the International Red Cross within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you do not surrender, you will be responsible for your
fate. There will be a blood bath,'' said the Voice of Tigers radio,
monitored in the northern Sri Lankan town of Vavuniya. ''This is
your last chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Friday deadline came soon after the rebels opened a new
front in the east, forcing the military to spread its soldiers to
guard areas where fighting had previously been sporadic.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels -- who have fought a 17-year war to establish an
independent homeland in the island's north and east for minority
Tamils -- are trying to recapture the city they used as a capital
from 1990-95.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate comment from the Sri Lankan government on
the rebel threat. But President Chandrika Kumaratunga has said in
newspaper interviews that her troops are in control of two-thirds
of the Jaffna peninsula and there was no question of a withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Neighboring India and the United States support a Norwegian
effort to bring warring sides into peace talks in an effort to
avoid a bloody Jaffna siege, a top American diplomat said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one that I know of has an answer'' to whether that will
happen, U.S. Undersecretary of State Thomas Pickering told
journalists in New Delhi. ''I know that Norway is continuing its
contacts in an effort to try to avoid that.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Washington and New Delhi were supporting the Norwegian
initiative of staying in touch with both parties to encourage them
to hold discussions.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel broadcast is part of the ''psychological warfare''
against the soldiers, said H.K. Dua, an aide to Indian Prime
Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
   India has offered to help evacuate Sri Lankan troops if asked,
but has said it will not commit its own troops to the fight.
</P>
<P>
   New Delhi committed forces to Sri Lanka in 1987 to help enforce
a peace accord between the government and the rebels, but withdrew
its troops after more than 1,000 deaths at the hand of the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The government's chief spokesman, Ariya Rubasinghe, said in a
faxed statement that troops backed by artillery and air cover
repulsed a rebel attack near Jaffna on Wednesday. He said 10 rebels
were killed, while eight soldiers died and 47 were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting continued Thursday but was not as intense as on
Wednesday, when the rebels fired mortars on an army camp and an air
force base, according to the Sri Lankan government and TamilNet, a
Web site that provides the rebels' perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from the military and the rebels cannot be verified
because neither side allows journalists into the war zone. The Sri
Lankan government also censors all news about the war and the
security situation.
</P>
<P>
   A land mine exploded Thursday in Vavuniya, killing two Tamil
politicians, local police said.
</P>
<P>
   No one claimed responsibility for the attack. But similar
killings in the past have been blamed on the rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-25-00 2046 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
