<HEADLINE> Clinton: I'm Not Job Hunting Yet  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD AIR FORCE ONE (AP) -- President Clinton says he's not
trying very hard to line up a new job to launch his post-White
House career.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with reporters aboard his presidential jet Thursday,
Clinton said he is more focused on building his library, museum and
policy center in Little Rock, Ark., than on getting his next job.
</P>
<P>
   He said he tells those who approach him, ''Come see me in
January.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I've really not done very much,'' Clinton said. He said his
library plans are a higher priority ''because you don't want it to
take forever and a day to get started.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not say how many offers he has entertained. But he
brushed aside rumors that he might go to work for DreamWorks SKG,
run by his friends Steven Spielberg, Jeffrey Katzenberg and David
Geffen.
</P>
<P>
   ''Literally, the only thing I heard about that was in the
newspaper,'' Clinton said. ''Nobody has ever talked to me about it.
I've certainly never talked to anybody about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said that, one month later, he still hears about
the short film he did last month lampooning his lame duck days in
the White House. ''I've had more comments about that than anything
I've done,'' he said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   The president spoke as his jet was taking off from Providence,
R.I., where he attended a memorial service for the son of Derek
Shearer, a longtime friend who advised his 1992 campaign on
economic policy. Clinton lingered in the press cabin during
takeoff, perched on a tabletop with no seat belt.
</P>
</TEXT>
