<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 29 Freed U.N. Peacekeepers Return  </HEADLINE>
By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Freed U.N. peacekeepers complained
Thursday of harsh treatment at the hands of their rebel captors and
said injured peacekeepers still being held are not being given
medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   The 29 U.N. peacekeepers, who were freed earlier this week on
the border with neighboring Liberia, were flown back to Sierra
Leone on Thursday to rejoin their units. Some 260 peacekeepers are
still being held by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The freed peacekeepers, all from Zambia, said their captive
colleagues are not receiving proper medical treatment at the rebel
camps and villages in eastern Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   One peacekeeper, who declined to give his name, said the injured
were becoming weaker by the day due to a lack of care.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials have put the number of wounded at 30 to 40. The
freed peacekeepers said they could not give any figures because the
captives are being held in several different places.
</P>
<P>
   When the peacekeepers were captured, a group of 50 was crammed
into a 15-seat bus and driven to a tiny village where they were
kept for three weeks, the soldiers said.
</P>
<P>
   Peacekeepers released earlier have spoken of being tied up, and
receiving as little as one banana or one mango a day for food.
</P>
<P>
   The 29 peacekeepers are the most recent group of U.N. captives
to be freed by Revolutionary United Front rebels, who seized nearly
500 U.N. hostages more than three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have released 233 peacekeepers. Most of the remaining
hostages are also from Zambia, according to U.N. spokesman David
Wimhurst.
</P>
<P>
   Liberian President Charles Taylor, who has close ties to the
rebels, has been helping negotiate the freedom of the peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Wimhurst expressed hope that more releases would take place in
advance of a regional summit this weekend in Nigeria, which is
expected to focus on the turmoil in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. spokesman also expressed condolences for two
journalists killed in an ambush by the rebels on Wednesday, Miguel
Gil Moreno de Mora, a cameramen for Associated Press Television
News, and Kurt Schork, a correspondent for Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   ''The deaths have shocked and saddened us all,'' Wimhurst said.
''These two men were both very fine journalists and experienced war
correspondents and their loss is being felt far beyond this
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Reuters journalists were also injured in Wednesday's attack
near Rogberi Junction, 50 miles northeast of Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-government troops and the rebels have clashed repeatedly in
recent weeks, but no other shooting incidents were reported over
the past 24 hours, Wimhurst said.
</P>
<P>
   About 11,000 U.N. peacekeepers are now in Sierra Leone, seeking
to stabilize a country devastated by a civil war that began in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the British government said Thursday that Sierra
Leone has pledged to stop using child soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The use of fighters under 18 was widespread during the civil
war, with both rebels and the government forces including children
their ranks.
</P>
<P>
   The Foreign Office said Britain's High Commissioner to Sierra
Leone, Alan Jones, had won assurances from Sierra Leonean president
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah that all soldiers aged under 18 would be
demobilized from pro-government forces and sent home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-25-00 2055 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000525.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands Protest Election in Peru  </HEADLINE>
By MONTE HAYES
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Hundreds of protesters attacked Peru's
election headquarters Thursday, breaking windows with rocks and
sledge hammers and burning tires at the front door, to demand
postponement of the presidential runoff.
</P>
<P>
   President Alberto Fujimori is pushing ahead with Sunday's vote
despite threats of international isolation, violent protests and a
foe who refuses to take part. Challenger Alejandro Toledo again
demanded a delay so international monitors can guarantee a fair
election.
</P>
<P>
   If the voting takes places, ''Alberto Fujimori's government will
be illegitimate, a source of permanent instability, and I don't
think it can last more than six to 12 months,'' Toledo said
Thursday prior to a huge rally in the northern fishing port of
Chimbote.
</P>
<P>
   The National Election Board confirmed Thursday that the runoff
would take place Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, the joint delegation from the U.S.-based National
Democratic Institute and Carter Center canceled plans to monitor
the runoff.
</P>
<P>
   ''The election on May 28 will not meet minimal international
standards for a credible, democratic election,'' said Barry Levitt,
a senior political analyst with the delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Police used tear gas and water cannons to clear out tens of
thousands of workers and university students who clogged Lima's
colonial downtown in response to a call from leftist-led unions.
Protests also took place in Arequipa, Peru's second-largest city
and a bastion of anti-Fujimori sentiment, and Cuzco, a tourist
mecca high in the Andes.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on the offices of the National Election Board came
after officials said software for tabulating votes successfully
passed a second test Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Monitors from the Organization of American States agreed that
test results indicated the new software was capable of eliminating
the problems presented in the first test over the weekend. But they
insisted the elections be postponed at least 10 days to give their
own experts time to evaluate the software.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's running mate, Francisco Tudela, said that any
decision rests with the National Election Board, not the
government. Fujimori's appointees control the board. He blamed
Toledo for creating the conditions that have put in doubt the
legitimacy of Sunday's election.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union added its voice to those of foreign
governments and international organizations calling for a
postponement.
</P>
<P>
   A victory on Sunday would bring the iron-fisted Fujimori a third
five-year term in power.
</P>
<P>
   ''The victory would be viewed as illegitimate,'' said Arturo
Porzecanski, chief economist for the Americas at the New York
financial firm ING Barings. ''I think the U.S. government, European
governments and many Latin American governments will distance
themselves from Peru in various ways -- diplomatically, in trade, in
financial support. I see isolation descending on Peru.''
</P>
<P>
   He said international sentiment is far different from 1992 when
Fujimori temporarily shut down Congress and the Supreme Court,
accusing them of blocking his efforts to battle leftist guerillas
and undertake economic reforms. At the time, Porzecanski said, many
governments were sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Three new polls released Thursday gave Fujimori a lead of 8 to
10 percentage points over Toledo, who insists he remains a
candidate but won't take part in Sunday's vote. Pollsters said
Toledo had lost support because he was focusing on denouncing fraud
instead of dealing with issues viewed as more important by voters
such as creating jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Within Fujimori's government, hard-liners linked to the armed
forces appeared to be edging out moderates who were pushing to
postpone the runoff.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government doesn't seem to be trying to find a way to
justify the postponement, but instead is beginning the job of
damage control,'' said political analyst Mirko Lauer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-25-00 2132 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
