<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chilean Military Accepts Ruling  </HEADLINE>
By EDUARDO GALLARDO
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Chile's top military commander on
Thursday said the country's armed forces laments but accepts a
court ruling that stripped Gen. Augusto Pinochet of his immunity
from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Army chief Gen. Ricardo Izurieta's remarks appeared likely to
ease tensions stemming from the Pinochet case, as the military
retains considerable political clout in a country it ruled
uncontested under Pinochet for 17 years until 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Izurieta said the military also fully supports civilian
President Ricardo Lagos, a socialist who was jailed for a time
under Pinochet's dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos' government has refused to interfere in legal actions
against Pinochet, saying they are matters for the courts. Pinochet
followers insist Lagos can and should protect the retired general.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's older son, also named Augusto, insisted Thursday that
Lagos should help his embattled father -- or face a crisis similar
to the one in which Pinochet toppled elected Marxist President
Salvador Allende in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   His father's situation ''is planting the seed of a deep division
among Chileans, and when this happens, the result may be a
situation like the one in September 1973,'' Pinochet's son said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of coup, Chile faced a major political and economic
crisis, marked by strong and often violent political clashes.
</P>
<P>
   The Santiago Court of Appeals voted behind closed doors Tuesday,
and although it did not immediately disclose its decision, it was
quickly leaked: the vote was 13-9 to strip Pinochet of his
congressional immunity, paving the way for his prosecution on human
rights charges.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the decision was leaked, Gen. Izurieta visited the
ailing 84-year-old former ruler in his heavily guarded Santiago
residence, a visit he described today as a show of ''institutional
support'' for Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   According to an official report, 3,191 people died or
disappeared under Pinochet's 1973-90 regime. More than 100 lawsuits
have been filed against him stemming from that era.
</P>
<P>
   Should the Supreme Court uphold the ruling against Pinochet, he
would face prosecution for the disappearance of 19 of 75 victims of
the so-called ''Caravan of Death,'' a military group that toured
several cities soon after the coup, dragging prisoners from jail
and executing them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-25-00 2210 </TRAILER>
