<DOCNO> APW20000525.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Meets Party Leaders  </HEADLINE>
By DARLENE SUPERVILLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- It's time to work, not panic, despite
lagging poll figures for Al Gore, Democratic officials from around
the country said Thursday. The likely Democratic presidential
nominee told supporters he faces ''a good, healthy, hard fight''
that he will win.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made the comments after meeting the Democratic officials
for a combination strategy session and pep rally.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody said it is terrible. Everybody understands that this is
going to be a long campaign,'' said Mark Brewer, Michigan
Democratic chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Gore acknowledged the tough campaign, but reassured supporters
he will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got a real good healthy hard fight ahead of us and we're
going to win it and we're going to win it solidly,'' Gore told
several hundred at a Democratic National Committee fund-raiser
Thursday night expected to bring in $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Gore privately addressed 72 Democratic leaders from 34
states, and took questions and answers about everything from health
care to George W. Bush's $460 billion tax-cut plan, according to
Brewer.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer described the gathering as relaxed, and others said there
was little concern that Gore's ''message'' might not be reaching
voters, while his Republican rival appears to be doing well among
Americans on issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't matter whether he gets (his message) across or not
now, it will matter after the convention, it will matter after
Labor Day,'' said Paul Berendt, Washington state Democratic
chairman. ''You don't fight the battle in May that you fight in
October.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, at a YMCA, the vice president added to his plans for
working families by proposing a tax credit to help them enroll
young people in after-school programs. Bush, too, has been
emphasizing education.
</P>
<P>
   ''Trouble doesn't stop when a child becomes a teen-ager,'' said
Gore, who has raised four.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic presidential contender also said he wants every
school to stay open late and for the government to ''dramatically''
increase funding for the school-based 21st Century Learning Centers
that help communities provide programs after school and during
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''Schools shouldn't close their doors when children need them
the most,'' Gore told about 100 parents, children and employees
gathered in a gym at the Donelson-Hermitage YMCA.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the proposals would help up to 10 million young
people.
</P>
<P>
   He previously had promised to invest $115 billion in education
over 10 years on various proposals, including universal preschool,
expanded Head Start, new schools and teacher bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's address to the party leaders came during a long-planned
meeting as recent polls show him 5 to 10 points behind Bush
nationally and down in some key states, and as some party officials
have questioned the low-key campaign he has run since sealing the
nomination in March.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the chairmen were at least outwardly unconcerned.
</P>
<P>
   Putting it in folksy terms, Molly Beth Malcolm, Democratic
chairwoman from Bush's home state of Texas, said, ''Bush is so new
and he's a nice guy, but he's one of those guys you want to go out
and date in college. You know you'll have a good time, but he's not
who anybody wants to marry.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer said Gore's poll numbers were reminiscent of President
Clinton's at various points in the 1992 and 1996 campaigns, as well
as President Bush's against Michael Dukakis in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   And Barbara Kay Allen, North Carolina chairwoman, said she
thinks Gore is in good shape. ''He shouldn't peak too early. He
shouldn't spend money too totally upfront, and he's been wise about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said it is a good idea for a national campaign to
involve state party chairmen.
</P>
<P>
   ''You shouldn't send teams from Washington into rural areas of a
state and tell people what to do. This campaign gets that,'' Allen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the YMCA address, delivered in a gym decorated with the
water-colored rainbows and tissue-paper flowers of the children who
play there, a smiling Gore spent a few minutes watching 10 kids
play basketball before he joined them on the hard court.
</P>
<P>
   He asked them what they would be doing if they didn't come to
the center. ''Stupid stuff,'' said one.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks on education -- an issue that Bush also is
focusing on -- Gore ran though a list of statistics to bolster his
case for improving and expanding after-school programs.
</P>
<P>
   In seven of 10 households, he said, both parents work all day.
The number of single-parent families has quadrupled in the past
three decades and at least 5 million children are left unsupervised
at home after school each week, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also repeated a Justice Department finding
that youngsters are most at risk of being victimized by crime or
drugs after school -- between the hours of 3 p.m. and 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ''Government doesn't raise children, families do,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ''No policy proposal can teach a child right from wrong ... but
we can make it easier, not harder, to be a strong family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
