<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ross Shelves Medical School Plan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASPER, Wyo. (AP) -- Blaming opposition from the medical
profession, Caribbean-based Ross University has shelved plans to
build a two-year medical school in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   The decision closes a nearly two-year-long chapter in local
economic development that sparked local, state and national debates
over foreign medical schools opening branches on U.S. soil.
</P>
<P>
   ''The decision to delay the project for the foreseeable future
was based on the simple fact that the university cannot afford to
invest in Wyoming when the object of the investment, new students,
will not be given the same opportunities as our students in
Dominica,'' Ross University President Neal Simon said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ross University School of Medicine is accredited in the
Commonwealth of Dominica.
</P>
<P>
   Ross faced opposition from some in the medical profession who
questioned the school's standards and chances of winning
accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   The Wyoming Medical Society last year asked the American Medical
Association to oppose the plan. It would have meant the first
for-profit medical school to be built in the U.S. in nearly 90
years.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Ross University: http://www.rossmed.edu.dm/
</P>
</TEXT>
