<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greene County twins accused of sexually abusing, filming young boys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSTON, N.Y.(AP) -- Twenty-two-year-old twin brothers from were
indicted Thursday on charges they sodomized and sexually abused 2-
and 5-year-old young boys, then put the acts on film.
</P>
<P>
   Ulster County District Attorney Donald A. Williams said the
investigation against Jason and Mark Vogt of Ancram, 20 miles east
of Kingston, was continuing and that a grand jury would continue to
review evidence against them during next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Vogt faces charges including sodomy, sexual abuse, using a
child in a sexual performance and possessing a sexual performance
by a child, all felonies involving a 2-year-old child. Jason Vogt
faces charges including sodomy involving sexual intercourse with a
5-year-old child, sodomy involving a 2-year-old child, sexual abuse
involving both a 5-year-old child and 2-year-old child and
possessing a sexual performance by a child, all felonies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Its incomprehensible ... to have two twin brothers allegedly
engage in these acts,'' Williams told the Kingston Daily Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   One of the defense attorneys, William R.S. Myers of Woodstock
said ''it's not often you see someone at college level being
charged with these types of offenses. Unfortunately, it happens
more often than we realize, but not by this type of a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Both brothers were recently enrolled at New Paltz state college.
</P>
<P>
   Searches of the Vogts' parents' home, a residence in Kingston,
and Jason Vogt's car turned up videotapes, photographs, and
numerous downloaded computer images depicting deviant sexual
intercourse with adults and children, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The sodomy charges that they currently face carry a maximum
sentence of 25 years in state prison.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said four children were involved in the alleged acts
but that the evidence points to sexual contact with only two of
them and that Jason Vogt faces similar charges in a neighboring
county and in a neighboring state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
