<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Astros 10, Phillies 6  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- Jeff Bagwell, Ken Caminiti and Mitch Meluskey
each hit two-run homers, and Richard Hidalgo had a solo shot as the
Houston Astros rallied twice Thursday night to beat the
Philadelphia Phillies 10-6.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Burrell, who made his major league debut a night earlier,
hit his first career homer, and Bobby Abreu and Desi Relaford also
connected for the Phillies. Burrell, the No. 1 pick in the 1998
amateur draft, went 1-for-4.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 84 home runs have been hit in 22 games at Enron
Field, 42 by the Astros. Last year, 118 were hit all season in the
Astrodome, 65 by Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Elarton (3-1) won despite allowing six runs and seven hits
-- three of them homers -- in six innings. Joe Slusarki finished with
one-hit relief for his first save.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Ashby (2-5) was tagged for eight runs, seven earned, and
nine hits in five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Phillies manager Terry Francona was ejected in the third for
arguing balls and strikes with plate umpire Doug Eddings, the first
ejection of a Phillie this season. Coach Chuck Cottier was ejected
in the ninth inning for arguing a call at first base.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia, which wasted 2-0 and 4-3 leads, went ahead in the
first on Abreu's two-run homer, his third home run in two days.
</P>
<P>
   Houston took a 3-2 lead in the bottom half on Bagwell's two-run
shot and Hidalgo's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Relaford's two-run triple gave Philadelphia a 4-3 lead in the
fourth, but the Astros went ahead for good in the bottom half.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo's 15th homer tied it, Roger Cedeno hit a run-scoring
infield single to third, and another run scored on Burrell's
throwing error at first.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti homered in the fifth to make it 8-4. Burrell and
Relaford hit solo shots in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Meluskey homered in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Burrell is 3-for-9 with a home run, a triple and three RBIs
in two games. ... Cedeno injured his hand sliding into first on a
close play in the fourth and left the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
