<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mariners' Abbott Struck in Face  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Seattle Mariners pitcher Paul Abbott fractured
his nose when he was struck in the face by a broken bat in the
fourth inning of Thursday night's game against Baltimore and needed
eight stitches.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott's 0-1 pitch to Baltimore's Harold Baines was grounded
back to the mound, breaking the head of Baines' bat. As Abbott
lowered his hands to field the grounder, the broken piece of the
bat struck him on the right side of the face.
</P>
<P>
   The ball caromed off Abbott's left leg and rolled to Mariners'
first baseman John Olerud, who tagged Baines for the out.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've seen it happen to a third baseman, when the bat goes out
and keeps the third baseman from fielding the ball,'' Olerud said.
''I know bats can come real close to the pitcher. But it's real
scary -- a jagged piece coming at you with some force.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbott lay on the mound for several minutes before rising on his
own power. He left the field on a stretcher while much of the crowd
at Camden Yards cheered.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott, who was replaced by Frankie Rodriguez, allowed three
hits and one run in 3 1-3 innings and left with the score 1-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
