<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-25 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hijacker Killed After Plane Robbery  </HEADLINE>
By OLIVER TEVES
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- A crying man tried to hijack a
Philippine Airlines jet carrying 291 people Thursday, then robbed
everyone and jumped out of the plane wearing a homemade parachute.
His body was found later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   The hijacker moved from bathroom to bathroom toward the front of
the Airbus 330, complaining of a stomachache, finally reaching the
cockpit, where he announced the hijacking minutes before the
scheduled landing, passengers said.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a grenade and a pistol, the man -- who had donned a
ski mask and swimming goggles -- ordered the pilot of PAL Flight
PR812 to return to Davao City in the southern Philippines. The
pilot responded that he did not have enough fuel, Manila airport
general manager Antonio Gana said. Davao City is about 600 miles
from the capital, Manila.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the weeping and distraught hijacker fired a shot
inside the cockpit, perhaps accidentally, said Emmanuel Generoso,
one of the three pilots aboard, as tired-looking passengers
streamed off the plane behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was very tense,'' Generoso said. ''I don't think there's
any political implications there. He had family problems, he needed
the money, so that's what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The plane was depressurized to permit the hijacker to jump with
a homemade parachute while it circled 28 miles from Manila at 6,000
feet, PAL spokesman Rolando Estabillo said. Police searched the
hilly area after he jumped.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers recovered the body of hijacker, identified as Augusto
Lakandula, in a heavily forested area after residents reported
seeing a man in a parachute landing on Thursday afternoon, Gen.
Jose Lachica said.
</P>
<P>
   His body was found in the town of Real, Quezon province, about
40 miles east of Manila, radio reports said.
</P>
<P>
   The improvised parachute was with him but not the bag of money
he took from the others aboard the plane, Lachica said.
</P>
<P>
   The hijacking recalled the case of the legendary D.B. Cooper,
who took over a Northwest Orient Airlines flight on Nov. 24, 1971,
demanding $200,000. After getting the money, he parachuted from the
plane over Washington state. He hasn't been heard from since,
although $5,880 of his loot was found on the banks of the Columbia
River in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   A rash of similar skyjackings followed, but the culprits were
caught.
</P>
<P>
   ''D.B. Cooper was the only one who was ever successful hijacking
and we don't even know if he survived,'' said Dan Poynter, author
of ''Parachuting: The Skydiver's Handbook.'' ''For somebody to go
out the side door of that aircraft, I just think he's probably a
skydiver and there aren't that many skydivers in the Philippines.''
</P>
<P>
   Passengers said the man collected all the money he could from
passengers before jumping.
</P>
<P>
   ''D.B. Cooper extorted money and this guy robbed the passengers,
which is an interesting twist,'' Poynter said. ''You can get the
money and get out quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   A flight attendant said he opened the door and even had to push
the man out. Mike Turoff, a commercial pilot in Houston and
co-author with Poynter, said the Airbus can slow down to below 200
mph but that is still more than twice the recommended speed for
skydiving.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you try to get out on your own, you really need a running
start,'' Turoff said. ''Pity this flight attendant that helped him.
Talk about being in mortal danger.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the body was found, the pilot Generosa said he doubted
the man could have survived the jump. Turoff said it's possible but
very risky.
</P>
<P>
   The jet landed -- with the side door still open -- at the Manila
airport about 2{ hours after starting what should have been a
90-minute trip, and all 277 passengers and 13 crew left the plane
safely, PAL said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-25-00 2342 </TRAILER>
